{"title_page": "Rob Flockhart (rugby union)", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Rob Flockhart\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Rob W. Flockhart\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = \n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Boroughmuir RFC|Boroughmuir]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province =\n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs = [[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]]\n| ru_coachyears = 1998-99\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = \n| ru_refereecomps =\n| ru_refereeapps = \n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 2016\n   | term_end      = 2018\n   | predecessor        = [[Ed Crozier]]\n   | successor          = Dee Bradbury\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 127th\n }}\n}}\n'''Rob Flockhart''' is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] former [[rugby union]] player. He was the 127th President of the Scottish Rugby Union.<ref name=\"auto1\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf</ref>\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nHe played for [[Boroughmuir RFC|Boroughmuir]]. As SRU President he recalled this time at the Edinburgh club when opening the 2016 [[Melrose Sevens]]: \"The profile of sevens has never been higher and Melrose - where I have happy memories of representing Boroughmuir in the tournament in the 1970s \u2013 continue to play their part in extending its appeal through the quality and imagination of the guest sides invited to the Greenyards.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesouthernreporter.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/early-glimpse-2017-melrose-7s-line-757541|title=Early glimpse of 2017 Melrose 7s line-up|website=www.thesouthernreporter.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\n\nFlockhart coached the [[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]] side in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000578%252f19980128%252f530%252f0029&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe has been a citing commissioner for Six Nations Championship matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/match-commissioner-look-biting-incident-2352418|title=Match commissioner to look into biting incident - but ref's 'try' blunder angers Italians|date=February 6, 2006|website=walesonline}}</ref>\n\nHe as acted as a citing commissioner for European Cup and Challenge Cup matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sareferees.com/News/referees-to-21-october-2012/2829727/|title=SA Rugby Referees|website=sareferees.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epcrugby.com/report/glasgow-warriors-v-g-r-a-n-parma/|title=Glasgow Warriors v G.R.A.N Parma|website=European Professional Club Rugby}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a citing commissioner for the [[Pro12]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emeraldrugby.com/Guinness-Pro14/News.aspx?NewsID=848f2da7-56bb-4ded-aaf2-0f4e8afea397|title=Pro12 News - Emerald Rugby|website=www.emeraldrugby.com}}</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe was voted a Vice-President of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] in 2015, beating Ian Barr of Lasswade by four votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glasgowhawks.com/news/sru-agm-1470646.html|title=StackPath|website=www.glasgowhawks.com}}</ref>\n\nFlockhart became the 127th President of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]]. He served the first two-year term in office from [[List of Scottish Rugby Union Presidents|2016 to 2018]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn his election he said: \"I am very keen, having spent this past year learning to ensure that there is strong trust, between the stakeholders, the clubs, the Council and the Board, that is where we start. That allows us to move forward with the club game to develop it and make it more sustainable. I think now what Mark Dodson and the executive team have done in making sure the professional game is on a solid footing, is fantastic. It allows us, with the debt where it is, to start thinking about how we drive forward and sustain the domestic game in Scotland.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/16/08/22/scottish-rugby-union-appoints-first-two-year-term-president-2016-agm|title=Scottish Rugby Union appoints first two-year term President at 2016 AGM|website=Scottish Rugby Union}}</ref>\n\nDuring Flockhart's time as president the SRU received criticism for the way it handled the sacking of their Director of Rugby, Keith Russell - the father of Scotland international [[Finn Russell]] - and the introduction of 'Agenda 3' which created an Edinburgh-centric national professional league competition, the Super 6, with 3 of the 6 sides coming from the capital - and no sides from the cities of Glasgow, Aberdeen, Dundee or Inverness.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/16399019.outgoing-sru-president-rob-flockhart-offers-apology-for-cloud-over-scottish-rugby/|title=Outgoing SRU president Rob Flockhart offers apology for 'cloud over Scottish Rugby'|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref>\n\nIn his annual report address to the SRU delegates, Flockhart stated: \"Over the last six weeks or so there\u2019s been a cloud over Scottish Rugby, I believe caused by two things: Firstly, the findings of the employment tribunal in relation to our former director of domestic rugby Keith Russell \u2013 I want to reassure you that through Council and board we will learn the lessons from the tribunal findings, we will implement recommendations from the review undertaken by Lesley Thomson, Scotland\u2019s former solicitor general. And I want to take this opportunity today to apologise to you all for the manner in which these matters have transpired. We must do better in this regard. Secondly, the concern and uncertainty surrounding Agenda 3. Agenda 3 was only ever a response to a recognition by many of our clubs and those volunteers in them that change is needed if our game is to survive and flourish. Ladies and gentlemen, we need to resolve these reservations, those concerns and those uncertainties and I hope that today we can go some way towards that.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe was bullish about the finances of the SRU. \"It\u2019s hugely pleasing. It helps drive Agenda 3, but the whole change in the past decade has been absolutely remarkable. The idea that we were so strung up with debt that it was difficult to do any forward planning until the debt was reduced means that the financial results allows us to show that we can handle debt and focus on future projects. There have been eight consecutive sell-outs at BT Murrayfield. 67,000 at the Samoa game. The performances of the Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s national teams, as well as Glasgow and Edinburgh, have all contributed to these recent figures; you don\u2019t get to turn over \u00a357 million unless there are big crowds at the very biggest games and successful teams are at the root of that. The turnover means that we can fund better professional teams but more importantly, we can fund club investment and the intention is to put more and more into the domestic game. The three strands of Agenda 3 \u2013 the Finance, Performance and Participation \u2013 money is needed for all of these. When I was elected I promised that I would try and brings clubs to the forefront of everything that happened at BT Murrayfield, which I think there\u2019s no denying has been the focus. Clubs wanted change and that\u2019s what Agenda 3 has tried to produce. There will be more discussion of course, and that\u2019s absolutely welcome; the finance allows other things to happen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scrummagazine.com/rob-flockhart-looks-back-on-his-time-as-scottish-rugby-president/|title=Rob Flockhart looks back on his time as Scottish Rugby President|first=Gavin|last=Harper|date=August 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flockhart, Rob}}\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Boroughmuir RFC players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Rob Flockhart\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Rob W. Flockhart\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = \n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Boroughmuir RFC|Boroughmuir]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province =\n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs = [[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]]\n| ru_coachyears = 1998-99\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = \n| ru_refereecomps =\n| ru_refereeapps = \n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 2016\n   | term_end      = 2018\n   | predecessor        = [[Ed Crozier]]\n   | successor          = Dee Bradbury\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 127th\n }}\n}}\n'''Rob Flockhart''' is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] former [[rugby union]] player. He was the 127th President of the Scottish Rugby Union.<ref name=\"auto1\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf</ref>  \n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nHe played for [[Boroughmuir RFC|Boroughmuir]]. As SRU President he recalled this time at the Edinburgh club when opening the 2016 [[Melrose Sevens]]: \"The profile of sevens has never been higher and Melrose - where I have happy memories of representing Boroughmuir in the tournament in the 1970s \u2013 continue to play their part in extending its appeal through the quality and imagination of the guest sides invited to the Greenyards.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesouthernreporter.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/early-glimpse-2017-melrose-7s-line-757541|title=Early glimpse of 2017 Melrose 7s line-up|website=www.thesouthernreporter.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\n\nFlockhart coached the [[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]] side in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000578%252f19980128%252f530%252f0029&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe has been a citing commissioner for Six Nations Championship matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/match-commissioner-look-biting-incident-2352418|title=Match commissioner to look into biting incident - but ref's 'try' blunder angers Italians|date=February 6, 2006|website=walesonline}}</ref>\n\nHe as acted as a citing commissioner for European Cup and Challenge Cup matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sareferees.com/News/referees-to-21-october-2012/2829727/|title=SA Rugby Referees|website=sareferees.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epcrugby.com/report/glasgow-warriors-v-g-r-a-n-parma/|title=Glasgow Warriors v G.R.A.N Parma|website=European Professional Club Rugby}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a citing commissioner for the [[Pro12]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emeraldrugby.com/Guinness-Pro14/News.aspx?NewsID=848f2da7-56bb-4ded-aaf2-0f4e8afea397|title=Pro12 News - Emerald Rugby|website=www.emeraldrugby.com}}</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe was voted a Vice-President of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] in 2015, beating Ian Barr of Lasswade by four votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glasgowhawks.com/news/sru-agm-1470646.html|title=StackPath|website=www.glasgowhawks.com}}</ref>\n\nFlockhart became the 127th President of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]]. He served the first two year term in office from [[List of Scottish Rugby Union Presidents|2016 to 2018]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn his election he said: \"I am very keen, having spent this past year learning to ensure that there is strong trust, between the stakeholders, the clubs, the Council and the Board, that is where we start. That allows us to move forward with the club game to develop it and make it more sustainable. I think now what Mark Dodson and the executive team have done in making sure the professional game is on a solid footing, is fantastic. It allows us, with the debt where it is, to start thinking about how we drive forward and sustain the domestic game in Scotland.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/16/08/22/scottish-rugby-union-appoints-first-two-year-term-president-2016-agm|title=Scottish Rugby Union appoints first two-year term President at 2016 AGM|website=Scottish Rugby Union}}</ref>\n\nDuring Flockhart's time as President the SRU received criticism for the way it handled the sacking of their Director of Rugby, Keith Russell - the father of Scotland international [[Finn Russell]] - and the introduction of 'Agenda 3' which created an Edinburgh-centric national professional league competition, the Super 6, with 3 of the 6 sides coming from the capital - and no sides from the cities of Glasgow, Aberdeen, Dundee or Inverness.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/16399019.outgoing-sru-president-rob-flockhart-offers-apology-for-cloud-over-scottish-rugby/|title=Outgoing SRU president Rob Flockhart offers apology for 'cloud over Scottish Rugby'|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref>\n\nIn his annual report address to the SRU delegates, Flockhart stated: \"Over the last six weeks or so there\u2019s been a cloud over Scottish Rugby, I believe caused by two things: Firstly, the findings of the employment tribunal in relation to our former director of domestic rugby Keith Russell \u2013 I want to reassure you that through Council and board we will learn the lessons from the tribunal findings, we will implement recommendations from the review undertaken by Lesley Thomson, Scotland\u2019s former solicitor general. And I want to take this opportunity today to apologise to you all for the manner in which these matters have transpired. We must do better in this regard. Secondly, the concern and uncertainty surrounding Agenda 3. Agenda 3 was only ever a response to a recognition by many of our clubs and those volunteers in them that change is needed if our game is to survive and flourish. Ladies and gentlemen, we need to resolve these reservations, those concerns and those uncertainties and I hope that today we can go some way towards that.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe was bullish about the finances of the SRU. \"It\u2019s hugely pleasing. It helps drive Agenda 3, but the whole change in the past decade has been absolutely remarkable. The idea that we were so strung up with debt that it was difficult to do any forward planning until the debt was reduced means that the financial results allows us to show that we can handle debt and focus on future projects. There have been eight consecutive sell-outs at BT Murrayfield. 67,000 at the Samoa game. The performances of the Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s national teams, as well as Glasgow and Edinburgh, have all contributed to these recent figures; you don\u2019t get to turn over \u00a357 million unless there are big crowds at the very biggest games and successful teams are at the root of that. The turnover means that we can fund better professional teams but more importantly, we can fund club investment and the intention is to put more and more into the domestic game. The three strands of Agenda 3 \u2013 the Finance, Performance and Participation \u2013 money is needed for all of these. When I was elected I promised that I would try and brings clubs to the forefront of everything that happened at BT Murrayfield, which I think there\u2019s no denying has been the focus. Clubs wanted change and that\u2019s what Agenda 3 has tried to produce. There will be more discussion of course, and that\u2019s absolutely welcome; the finance allows other things to happen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scrummagazine.com/rob-flockhart-looks-back-on-his-time-as-scottish-rugby-president/|title=Rob Flockhart looks back on his time as Scottish Rugby President|first=Gavin|last=Harper|date=August 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flockhart, Rob}}\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Boroughmuir RFC players]]\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: President \u2192 president, two year \u2192 two-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Flockhart_(rugby_union)"}
{"title_page": "Stade Albert Domec", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Stade Albert Domec\n| image                  =  [[File:Stade Albert Domec Entr\u00e9e.jpg|250px]]\n| caption                = The entrance to Stade Albert Domec\n| fullname               = Stade Albert Domec\n| former_names           = Stade de la P\u00e9pini\u00e8re (1899-1948)\n| location               = Carcassonne, France\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|43|13|4|N|2|21|52|E|display=inline,title|type:landmark}} \n| built                  = 1899\n| opened                 = 1899\n| renovated              = 2002, 2012\n| expanded               = \n| closed                 = \n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = \n| surface                = Grass\n| capacity               = 10,000\n| record_attendance      = 23,500 \n| dimensions             = \n| tenants             = [[AS Carcassonne]]<br />[[US Carcassonne]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Stade Albert Domec''' is a multi-use municipal [[stadium]] in [[Carcassonne]], [[France]]. It has a capacity of 10,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stadium-attendances.com/stade-albert-domec-carcassonne.htm|title=Stade Albert Domec Carcassonne|publisher=Stadium-attendances.com|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> It is the home ground of [[Pro D2]] rugby union club [[US Carcassonne|Union Sportive Carcassonnaise]] and [[Elite One Championship]] rugby league club [[AS Carcassonne|Association Sportive de Carcassonne XIII]]. It is also used by the association football club Football Agglom\u00e9ration Carcassonne for their big matches. Built in 1899, it is one of the oldest stadiums in France, and was renovated in 2002, and again in 2012 when US Carcassonne entered the Pro D2. The stadium is named after the French rugby union player [[Albert Domec]], who died 20 September 1948, and who represented [[France national rugby union team|France]] in 1939. The stadium is also equipped for athletics and has an eight lane 400m track.\n\nThe stadium has been used in [[Rugby League World Cup]]s. The ground has hosted many French rugby league championship and cup finals as well as French rugby league internationals, the first being in 1967 when [[Great Britain national rugby league team]] won 16\u201313 in front of 10,650 spectators\n\n== History ==\n\nFormerly called 'le stade de la Pepiniere' the ground was built and opened in 1899 and sits within the medieval castle walls of the city. In 1919 the rugby club paid 95,000 francs for the site then sold it to the local council a year later. The council built the two main stands that run along the length of the pitch each able to hold 3,000 spectators, floodlights and a cycle track were also installed. The stadium has been renovated twice since in 2002 and in 2012.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Delaney|first1=Trevor|title=The International Grounds of Rugby League|date=1995|publisher=Trevor R Delaney|isbn=978-0950998244|pages=154, 155}}</ref> The ground is named after the former [[US Carcassonne]] and French rugby union international player [[Albert Domec]] who played as a centre during the 1920s and 1930s. The stadium has a bronze statue of AS Carcassonne's most famous player, former captain of the [[France national rugby league team|French national rugby league team]], [[Puig Aubert]] at its entrance. The record attendance at the ground is 23,500 for the [[French rugby league championship]] final in 1949 between [[AS Carcassonne]] and [[Marseille XIII]].\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:PUIG.jpg|thumb|Stautue of Puig Albert outside ground]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:STADEALBERT.jpg|thumb|Main Stand]] -->\n\n== International Rugby League Matches ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Teams !! Score !! Attendance !! Competition\n|-\n| 22 January 1967 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 13-16 || 10,650 || Test Match\n|-\n| 24 December 1967 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|AUS}} || 10-3 || 4,193 || 