III Catalan]] || 12-5 || [[Lyon Villeurbanne]] || 13,500\n|-\n| 1956-57 || [[Marseille XIII]] || 11-0 || [[XIII Catalan]] || 16,633\n|-\n| 1958-59 || [[XIII Catalan]] || 7-0 || [[SO Avignon]] || 11,000\n|-\n| 1965-66 || [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]] || 22-7 || [[US Villeneuve]] || 10,067\n|-\n| 1972-73 || [[RC Saint-Gaudens]] || 22-8 || [[AS Carcassonne]] || 10,300\n|-\n| 1990-91 || [[RC Saint-Gaudens]] || 30-4 || [[Pia XIII]] || 6,000\n|-\n| 1993-94 || [[AS Saint Esteve]] || 14-12 || [[XIII Catalan]] || \n|-\n| 1996-97 || [[XIII Catalan]] || 25-24 || [[Limoux Grizzlies]] || 8,000\n|-\n| 1997-98 || [[AS Saint Esteve]] || 38-0 || [[SO Avignon]] || 7,000\n|-\n| 2001-02 || [[Villeneuve Leopards]] || 27-18 || [[Pia XIII]] || 8,500\n|-\n| 2002-03 || [[Villeneuve Leopards]] || 16-14 || [[Pia XIII]] || 7,000\n|-\n| 2003-04 || [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan|Union Treiziste Catalane]] || 36-24 || [[AS Carcassonne]] || 10,500\n|-\n| 2004-05 || [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan|Union Treiziste Catalane]] || 31-12 || [[Limoux Grizzlies]] || 11,000\n|-\n| 2005-06 || [[Pia XIII]] || 36-20 || [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]] || 9,344\n|-\n| 2006-07 || [[Pia XIII]] || 30-14 || [[AS Carcassonne]] || 5,500\n|-\n| 2007-08 || [[Limoux Grizzlies]] || 17-14 || [[RC Albi]] || 9,000\n|-\n| 2010-11 || [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]] || 27-18 || [[Pia XIII]] || 5,350\n|-\n| 2012-13 || [[SO Avignon]] || 38-37 || [[Limoux Grizzlies]] || 5,000\n|-\n| 2013-14 || [[Toulouse Olympique]] || 46-10 || [[AS Carcassonne]] || 6,763\n|-\n| 2014-15 || [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]] || 27-25 || [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]] || 4,124\n|-\n| 2015-16 || [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]] || 33-16 || [[Limoux Grizzlies]] || 4,200\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n*[[List of rugby league stadiums by capacity]]\n*[[List of rugby union stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Elite One Championship Stadiums}}\n{{Rugby League in France}}\n{{1985-88 RLWC Venues}}\n{{1989-1992 RLWC Venues}}\n{{2000 RLWC Venues}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albert Domec, Stade}}\n[[Category:Rugby league stadiums in France]]\n[[Category:Rugby union stadiums in France]]\n[[Category:Rugby League World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in France]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Aude]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1899]]\n\n\n{{France-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Stade Albert Domec\n| image                  =  [[File:Stade Albert Domec Entr\u00e9e.jpg|250px]]\n| caption                = The entrance to Stade Albert Domec\n| fullname               = Stade Albert Domec\n| former_names           = Stade de la P\u00e9pini\u00e8re (1899-1948)\n| location               = Carcassonne, France\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|43|13|4|N|2|21|52|E|display=inline,title|type:landmark}} \n| built                  = 1899\n| opened                 = 1899\n| renovated              = 2002, 2012\n| expanded               = \n| closed                 = \n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = \n| surface                = Grass\n| capacity               = 10,000\n| record_attendance      = 23,500 \n| dimensions             = \n| tenants             = [[AS Carcassonne]]<br />[[US Carcassonne]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Stade Albert Domec''' is a multi-use municipal [[stadium]] in [[Carcassonne]], [[France]]. It has a capacity of 10,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stadium-attendances.com/stade-albert-domec-carcassonne.htm|title=Stade Albert Domec Carcassonne|publisher=Stadium-attendances.com|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> It is the home ground of [[Pro D2]] rugby union club [[US Carcassonne|Union Sportive Carcassonnaise]] and [[Elite One Championship]] rugby league club [[AS Carcassonne|Association Sportive de Carcassonne XIII]]. It is also used by the association football club Football Agglom\u00e9ration Carcassonne for their big matches. Built in 1899, it is one of the oldest stadiums in France, and was renovated in 2002, and again in 2012 when US Carcassonne entered the Pro D2. The stadium is named after the French rugby union player [[Albert Domec]], who died 20 September 1948, and who represented [[France national rugby union team|France]] in 1939. The stadium is also equipped for athletics and has an eight lane 400m track.\n\nThe stadium has been used in [[Rugby League World Cup]]s. The ground has hosted many French rugby league championship and cup finals as well as French rugby league internationals, the first being in 1967 when [[Great Britain national rugby league team]] won 16\u201313 in front of 10,650 spectators\n\n== History ==\n\nFormerly called 'le stade de la Pepiniere' the ground was built and opened in 1899 and sits within the medieval castle walls of the city. In 1919 the rugby club paid 95,000 francs for the site then sold it to the local council a year later. The council built the two main stands that run along the length of the pitch each able to hold 3,000 spectators, floodlights and a cycle track were also installed. The stadium has been renovated twice since in 2002 and in 2012.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Delaney|first1=Trevor|title=The International Grounds of Rugby League|date=1995|publisher=Trevor R Delaney|isbn=978-0950998244|pages=154, 155}}</ref> The ground is named after the former [[US Carcassonne]] and French rugby union international player [[Albert Domec]] who played as a centre during the 1920s and 1930s. The stadium has a bronze statue of AS Carcassonne's most famous player, former captain of the [[France national rugby league team|French national rugby league team]], [[Puig Aubert]] at its entrance. The record attendance at the ground is 23,500 for the [[French rugby league championship]] final in 1949 between [[AS Carcassonne]] and [[Marseille XIII]].\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:PUIG.jpg|thumb|Stautue of Puig Albert outside ground]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:STADEALBERT.jpg|thumb|Main Stand]] -->\n\n== International Rugby League Matches ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Teams !! Score !! Attendance !! Competition\n|-\n| 22 January 1967 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 13-16 || 10,650 || Test Match\n|-\n| 24 December 1967 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|AUS}} || 10-3 || 4,193 || [[1967-68 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain and France]]\n|-\n| 21 November 1971 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} || 2-24 || 7,200 || [[1971 New Zealand rugby league tour of Great Britain and France]]\n|-\n| 20 March 1977 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|ENG}} || 28-15 || 12,000 || [[1977 European Rugby League Championship]]\n|-\n| 26 November 1978 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|AUS}} || 13-10 || 7,000 || [[1978-79 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain and France]]\n|-\n| 28 October 1979 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Papua New Guinea}} || 15-2 || 3,500 || Test Match\n|-\n| 20 February 1983 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 5-20 || 3,826 || Test Match\n|-\n| 13 December 1986 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|AUS}} || 0-52 || 5,000 || [[1985-1988 Rugby League World Cup]]\n|-\n| 8 February 1987 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 10-20 || 2,000 || Test Match\n|-\n| 15 November 1987 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Papua New Guinea}} || 21-4 || 5,000 || [[1985-1988 Rugby League World Cup]]\n|-\n| 19 November 1989 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} || 14-16 || 3,500 || [[1989 New Zealand rugby league tour of Great Britain and France]]\n|-\n| 3 December 1989 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} || 0-34 || 4,208 || [[1989-1992 Rugby League World Cup]]\n|-\n| 24 November 1991 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Papua New Guinea}} || 28-14 || 1,440 || [[1989-1992 Rugby League World Cup]]\n|-\n| 7 March 1993 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 6-48 || 5,500 || Test Match\n|-\n| 21 November 1993 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} || 11-36 || 3,500 || [[1993 New Zealand rugby league tour of Great Britain and France]]\n|-\n| 20 March 1994 || {{rl|FRA}} v {{rl|Great Britain}} || 4-12 || 7,000 || Test Match\n|-\n| 5 Mar