{"title_page": "The Call (2013 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Call\n| image          = The Call poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Brad Anderson (director)|Brad Anderson]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|Jeff Graup|Michael Luisi|Michael A. Helfant|Robert L. Stein|Bradley Gallo}}\n| screenplay     = Richard D'Ovidio\n| story          = {{ubl|Richard D'Ovidio|Nicole D'Ovidio|[[Jon Bokenkamp]]}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Halle Berry]]|[[Abigail Breslin]]|[[Morris Chestnut]]|[[Michael Eklund]]|[[David Otunga]]|[[Michael Imperioli]]}}\n| music          = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Thomas Yatsko]]\n| editing        = Avi Youabian\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[Stage 6 Films]]|Troika Pictures|[[WWE Studios]]|Amasia Entertainment|Apotheosis Media Group}}\n| distributor    = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|03|15}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 94:15 --><ref>{{cite web|title=''THE CALL'' (15)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/call-2013-1|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130624234542/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/call-2013-1|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 24, 2013|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=June 7, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $13 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=call2013.htm |title= The Call (2013)|website= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n| gross          = $68.6 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Call''''' is a 2013 American [[psychological thriller]] [[crime film]] directed by [[Brad Anderson (director)|Brad Anderson]] and written by Richard D'Ovidio. The film stars [[Abigail Breslin]] as Casey Welson, a teenage girl kidnapped by a [[serial killer]] and [[Halle Berry]] as Jordan Turner, a [[9-1-1]] operator, still suffering emotionally from a prior botched 9-1-1 call, who receives Casey's call. [[Morris Chestnut]], [[Michael Eklund]], [[Michael Imperioli]], and [[David Otunga]] also star. The story was originally envisioned as a television series, but D'Ovidio later rewrote it as a feature film. Filming began in July 2012 and spanned a period of 25 days, with all scenes being shot in [[California]], mainly [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] and [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]].\n\nA screening of ''The Call'' was held at the Women's International Film Festival hosted at the Regal South Beach theater on February 26, 2013. [[TriStar Pictures]] released it to theatres on March 15, 2013. Considered to be [[high-concept]] by many reviewers, the film proved a commercial success, grossing over $68 million against budget of $13 million. Halle Berry was nominated for Choice Movie Actress in a Drama at the [[Teen Choice Awards]] and Best Actress at the [[BET Awards]] while the film itself received mixed reviews from critics, but praised Berry and Breslin's performances and the film's suspense.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Los Angeles Police Department]] veteran [[9-1-1]] operator, Jordan Turner, receives a call one night, from a teenage girl, Leah Templeton, fearing for her life as a man breaks into her home. Jordan calmly advises her to conceal herself upstairs. When the call is disconnected, Jordan calls Leah back, a decision that costs Leah her life. The ringing phone gives her location away to the intruder. Jordan attempts to dissuade him from going further over the phone. He responds \"It's already done\" and hangs up, leaving her distraught.\n\nThe next day, Jordan sees a television report confirming that Leah has been murdered. Emotionally affected by the incident, Jordan tells her boyfriend, Officer Paul Phillips, that she can no longer handle field calls.\n\nSix months later, she is working as a trainer for 9-1-1 operators. Teenager Casey Welson is kidnapped from a mall parking garage by a man named Michael Foster after shopping with her friend, Autumn, and forced into the trunk of his car, a red [[Toyota Camry (XV30)|Toyota Camry LE]]. Casey had taken Autumn's [[TracFone|disposable phone]] after she accidentally left it in the mall, and uses it to call 9-1-1. A rookie operator, Brooke, receives the call but is unable to handle it, prompting Jordan to take over. However, Casey's use of a disposable Phase I phone means that her location cannot be determined by GPS, showing only the location of the Cell Tower the disposable is connected to.\n\nWhile Michael drives, Jordan guides Casey through knocking out a [[tail light]] and signaling people in nearby cars. One woman who sees Casey waving her arm out of the trunk of the car calls 9-1-1 on a phone with Phase II capabilities, allowing the police to narrow their search. When Casey tells Jordan that there are cans of paint in the trunk, Jordan has Casey pour the paint out of the taillight hole. This attracts the attention of another motorist, Alan Denado, but Michael knocks him out with a shovel, and assuming him to be dead stuffs Alan in the trunk of a black [[Lincoln Town Car|Lincoln Town Car Signature Limited]] with Casey.\n\nAlan reawakens in the trunk and begins screaming uncontrollably, and Michael stabs him, unfortunately Alan gives away an Escape Lever to Michael who rips it out. Michael stops at a gas station where Casey gets an idea to crawl out of the trunk and scream for help. A gas attendant attempts to bust the door open, but Michael sprays him with gasoline and throws a lighter at him, burning him.\n\nUpon arriving at his destination, Michael removes Casey from the trunk and finds the phone in her pocket, with 9-1-1 listening on the line. Through the phone, Jordan informs him that his identity is uncovered and advises him to surrender himself and not hurt the girl. Before smashing the phone, Michael responds, \"It's already done\", leading Jordan to realize that Michael is the same culprit who killed Leah six months prior.\n\nMeanwhile, Paul, accompanied by Officer Jake Devans and others in law enforcement, raid Michael's home, but find only his wife and children. Finding a photo of Michael and his sister, Melinda, they realize that Casey resembles her. Additionally, the house seen in the photo is eventually revealed by Michael's wife to have burned down, although a nearby cottage still remains. The police raid it, but find nobody there and leave.\n\nMichael begins to wash and cut Casey's hair. Determined to rescue Casey, Jordan drives to the secondary home where she finds a number of photos of Michael with his [[leukemia]]-stricken sister. Stepping outside, she recognizes sounds from an outdoor [[flagpole]]\u2014exactly the same sound she heard in the background in the final moments of the 9-1-1 call. She also finds a trap door amid dirt and scrub located where the primary house once stood. Jordan accidentally drops her cellphone down the cellar and climbs down in without calling the police.\n\nNavigating the cellar, Jordan hides from an emerging Michael. The cellar itself pieces together Michael's backstory. Michael had [[incest]]uous feelings towards Melinda and was distraught when she fell ill, lost all of her hair and died of leukemia. Michael has a prop head that he keeps in the cellar that he treats like his sister. He has also been scalping and killing young girls who have similar blond hair, trying to find scalps that match his sister's hair.\n\nJordan soon finds Casey strapped down to a foldable wheelchair and attacks Michael, as he begins to lacerate Casey's scalp. She frees Casey and both make an attempt to escape the cellar, during which Casey stabs Michael in the back with a pair of scissors. Michael pursues them and they are able to injure and kick him back down into the cellar, rendering him unconscious. While he is knocked out, they tie him to the same chair Casey was restrained to during captivity.\n\nWhen he regains consciousness, they inform him that they plan to [[starvation|leave him to die]] and claim that Casey had escaped, that she was found by Jordan in the woods, and that Michael disappeared. Michael pleads that they cannot just leave him there, but Jordan replies using Michael's own words, \"It's already done.\" Michael shouts insults at them, Jordan locks the door and leaves, avenging Leah's death.\n\n==Cast==\n{{divcol}}\n* [[Halle Berry]] as Jordan Turner, a 9-1-1 operator\n* [[Abigail Breslin]] as Casey Welson, a kidnapped teenager\n* [[Morris Chestnut]] as Officer Paul Phillips, Jordan's boyfriend\n* [[Michael Eklund]] as Michael Foster, Casey's kidnapper\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as Alan Denado, Michael's victim\n* [[David Otunga]] as Officer Jake Devan\n* [[Justina Machado]] as Rachel\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Z\u00fa\u00f1iga]] as Marco\n* [[Roma Maffia]] as Maddy\n* Evie Thompson as Leah Templeton\n* Denise Dowse as Flora\n* [[Ella Rae Peck]] as Autumn\n* [[Jenna Lamia]] as Brooke\n* Ross Gallo as Josh\n* Shawnee Badger as Melinda Foster\n* [[Tara Platt]] as Female Trainee\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Writing and casting===\n{{quote box\n|width = 30em\n|border = 1px\n|align=right\n|bgcolor=#c6dbf7\n|fontsize = 85%\n|title_bg =\n|title_fnt =\n|title =\n|quote = \"I thought, 'That's a world we've never seen before in a film.' You never get to see the other side of it. [They were playing some actual calls on the news segment, and] listening to the calls, I got a chill up my spine as I envisioned what was going on [on the other end of the phone], and I thought that it would be a great world to play into.\"\n|salign = right\n|source =\u2014Screenwriter Richard D'Ovidio on the radio segment that led him to write the screenplay for ''The Call''<ref name= \"Decker\" />\n}}\nScreenwriter Richard D'Ovidio was inspired to script the story after his wife heard an NPR segment with a 9-1-1 operator discussing her job. He began to research the subject and visited the Los Angeles Metropolitan Communications Dispatch Center (MCDC). Finding the center, which has backup generators, bulletproof windows, and a moat surrounding the building, to be \"pretty amazing,\" he decided to shed light on what he viewed as a previously overlooked occupation. The story was originally conceptualized as a television series titled ''The Hive'' (a reference to the constant calls and conversations sounding like bees buzzing), but D'Ovidio decided to redraft it as a film on realizing that \"the operators couldn't be the ones kicking in doors and going out into the field\" all the time. As a result, what was planned to be the pilot episode was expanded and revised as a movie.<ref name=\"Decker\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/62781/call-set-visit-report-part-one-writer-richard-dovidio-his-inspiration-research-and-more |author= Decker, Sean |date= January 14, 2013 |title= The Call Set Visit Report - Part One: Writer Richard D'Ovidio on His Inspiration, Research, and More! |publisher= Dread Central |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dwight-brown/the-call_b_2875451.html?ir=Entertainment |author= Brown, Dwight |date= March 15, 2013 |title= The Call |work= [[The Huffington Post]] |quote= Jordan (Berry) works in the L.A. 911 call center. They call it the hive, because with the constant din of conversations it sounds like bees at work. |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor most of the film, Berry's character, Turner, the 9-1-1 operator, does stay inside \"the hive\" before becoming actively involved in the search for Breslin's character, Welson, the kidnapped caller. D'Ovidio chose two female leads, explaining, \"I wanted strong women... I think it was appropriate here, since most 911 call operators are women.\"<ref name=\"Decker\" /> Berry remarked, \"I love the idea of being a part of a movie that was so empowering for women. We don't often get to play roles like this, where ordinary people become heroic and do something extraordinary.\"<ref name=\"Grant\">{{cite news |last= Grant |first= Kimberly |title= Berry, Chestnut Expound on ''The Call'' Roles - and more |work= South Florida Times |location= Fort Lauderdale |date= March 13, 2013 |url= http://www.sfltimes.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12684&Itemid=187 |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> D'Ovidio chose to tell the story from the perspective of two characters\u2014the operator and the caller\u2014believing that it would become repetitive if it focused on only one. As a result, he switched perspectives every ten pages when writing the screenplay. As well as collaborating on the story with his wife, Nicole and Jon Bokenkamp, he accepted suggestions from Berry, Breslin and Eklund: \"Halle came in with some great notes and Abigail and Michael and it started to flesh things out. I'm not one to say 'no' to a great suggested line of dialogue. It just makes me look better as a writer! I feel it's a very collaborative process, and some of the happiest accidents happen when you just listen to people. When someone comes up to you and says, 'Why don't we do it this way?' I think that it's important to listen.\"<ref name=\"Decker\" />\n\nChestnut, who plays Phillips, a police officer and Turner's boyfriend, prepared by riding along with Los Angeles police officers to observe what it is like to be an officer in a squad car<ref name=\"Grant\" /> and Berry prepared for the role by visiting a call center and observing the operators at work.<ref name=\"Decker\" /> She told a ''[[The Miami Herald|Miami Herald]]'' interviewer, \"You get a different perspective by doing research... You can't know what it's like to be a cop even though you've seen it in the movies. But nobody ever saw a 9-1-1 center. I thought they lived in the ground somewhere! It was interesting to see who they were and how they deal and how stressful it can be. I was a wreck watching them. They would just be as cool as can be doing their thing. I thought, 'I could never do this job.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Marr |first= Madeleine |title= Call 911! It's Halle Berry and Morris Chestnut |work= [[The Miami Herald]] |location= Miami |publisher= The McClatchy Company |date= March 10, 2013 |url= http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/03/10/3274730/call-911-its-halle-berry-and-morris.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nProducers scheduled for ''The Call'' to be filmed in Canada in June 2011 after they failed to make the cut for a California tax credit. With a low budget of $13 million, they settled on [[Ottawa, Ontario]], where director Anderson had just finished another project. However, the [[California Film Commission]] (CFC) called back nine months later and informed them that the waiting list had been largely cleared and that they now qualified for $1.9 million in tax deduction. According to Producer Michael Helfant, they were \"literally days from starting to put down a deposit.\" Berry was reportedly pleased with the news, having wanted to stay in Los Angeles and the CFC helped secure film locations for the project.<ref name=\"Verrier\">{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Verrier|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/mar/20/business/la-fi-ct-onlocation-20130320|title=A Fateful Call Keeps Filming of 'The Call' in L.A.|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWith a crew of roughly 120 persons, filming took a total of 25 days, spanning from July to August 2012. Car chase scenes were shot at [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] and a [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]] office building was modeled as the emergency dispatch center. The latter was also used for the scenes in which Welson is locked in the trunk of a car. Other filming locations include the [[Burbank Town Center]] on Magnolia Boulevard in [[Burbank, California]], [[Santa Clarita, California]] and the 170 Highway.<ref name=\"Verrier\" /> At one point, Berry was rushed to [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]] after falling headfirst on concrete while shooting a fight sequence. A spokesperson for Berry confirmed that she suffered a minor head injury and was taken to the hospital as a precaution, but she checked out healthy and was released.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2175149/Halle-Berry-rushed-hospital-accident-movie-set.html |title=Pictured: Halle Berry rushed to hospital 'after accident on movie set' |first=Sarah |last=Bull |work=[[Daily Mail]] |location=London |date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBerry told interviewer Kimberly Grant, \"The hard part for me was to try to stay connected to Phillips and Welson.\" This was because, Grant writes, \"she had to spend an entire day reading 21 pages of dialogue, rattling off in quick succession 911-operator jargon, that would be cut and edited to fit the film... In film terms, that means Berry performed for 21 minutes straight with no breaks, not an easy feat for any actor.\" Though she enjoyed working with Chestnut,<ref name=\"Zwecker\" /> Berry told Grant that it was difficult being unable to see her co-stars for most of the film: \"That was my constant challenge; to stay on such an emotional level [as Jordan], so that I would be on the same level as they [i.e., Casey and Officer Phillips] were. I used that feeling of frustration and of being stuck to fuel my character.\"<ref name=\"Grant\" />\n\n===Music===\nThe score of the film is composed by John Debney. Unlike the other films he composed with an orchestra, the film's score is completely filled with dark and intense electronic and synthesized elements. Although, he used little orchestral elements in the score.\n\n==Promotion and release==\n\n[[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] paid very little money to acquire U.S. distribution rights.<ref>https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120629005601/en/WWE-Studios-Enters-Hive-Troika-Pictures</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite journal |url= http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/03/16/friday-box-office-oz-the-call-burt-wonderstone/ |last= Smith |first= Grady |title= Box office update: ''Oz'' wins Friday with $11.4 million; ''The Call'' crushes ''Burt Wonderstone'' |journal= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 16, 2013 |location= New York |publisher= Time Inc. |page= }}</ref> But the film screened for a test audience in November 2012 and scores were even higher than anticipated, prompting Sony to give the film a wide theatrical release.<ref>https://variety.com/2013/film/news/sony-shuffles-carrie-the-call-1118064130/</ref>\n\nSpanning 94 minutes upon completion, the movie received an R rating for violence, disturbing content and some language.<ref name=\"Dargis\" /> Berry and Chestnut promoted the film at the ShowPlace ICON movie theater<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theybf.com/2013/03/01/getting-an-eyeful-morris-chestnut-halle-berry-roll-to-chicago-to-promote-the-call|author=Natasha|date=March 1, 2013|title= GETTING AN EYEFUL: Morris Chestnut & Halle Berry Roll To Chicago To Promote ''The Call''|publisher=[[Theybf.com]]|accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> at the red-carpet premiere in Chicago on February 28.<ref name=\"Zwecker\">{{cite news|last=Zwecker|first=Bill|title=Halle Berry says 'I was the lucky one' in Morris Chestnut love scenes|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=Chicago|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|date= March 12, 2013|url= http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/18808973-421/halle-berry-says-i-was-the-lucky-one-in-morris-chestnut-love-scenes.html|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> Berry also traveled to Rio to promote ''The Call'' in anticipation of its April 12 release in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news|title=Halle Berry Announces Brazilian Visit to Promote 'The Call'|work=Boxoffice|date= March 28, 2013|url=http://www.boxoffice.com/latest-news/2013-03-28-halle-berry-announces-brazilian-visit-to-promote-the-call|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Women's International Film Festival hosted a screening of ''The Call'' at the Regal South Beach theater on February 26, 2013.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://oceandrive.com/events |last= Caballero |first= Gustavo |title= Events / 'The Call' Red Carpet Screening |journal= Ocean Drive |location= Miami Beach, FL |publisher= |date= February 26, 2013 |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> Chestnut told the audience that he would sign on for a sequel, saying about Berry, \"I didn't get to kiss this woman enough!\" Berry added, \"I'm in the movie and even I was scared.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Marr|first=Madeleine|title=Will Matt Damon renew vows in Miami?|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|location=Miami|publisher=The McClatchy Company|date=February 28, 2013|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/02/28/3259330/will-matt-damon-renew-vows-in.html|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> The film was released in theatres on March 15 and on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc]] on June 25 of that same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Call|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Call-Blu-ray/70091/|publisher=[[Blu-ray]]|date=June 25, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> DVD extras included a [[featurette]] entitled \"Emergency Procedure: Making the Film\" and commentary from Abigail Breslin, Halle Berry, and other filmmakers. The Blu-ray version came with more features, including [[deleted scene]]s, an alternate ending, Michael Eklund's audition tape, featurettes entitled \"A Set Tour of The Hive and The Lair\" and \"Inside the Stunts\", as well as all of the original DVD content.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rawden|first=Jessica|title=The Call Will Hit Blu-ray And DVD In June|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Call-Hit-Blu-ray-DVD-June-37405.html|publisher=Cinema Blend|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n\nAccording to ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|Boxoffice]],'' ''The Call'' was expected to earn about $11\u201312 million on its opening weekend in 2,507 theaters across the United States but surpassed this by a significant margin and grossed $17 million in its first three days. This indicated good profits, as the film cost about $13 million to produce and Sony paid a much smaller amount to acquire U.S. distribution rights.<ref name=\"Smith\"/> With box office takings of over $68 million, ''The Call'' is [[WWE Studios]]' most commercially successful film to date, the previous top-grossing productions being ''[[See No Evil (2006 film)|See No Evil]],'' which stars [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] (Glenn Jacobs) ($19 million) and ''[[12 Rounds (film)|12 Rounds]],'' which stars [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[John Cena]] ($17 million).<ref name=\"Greaser\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/the-call-dials-up-wwes-film-biz-1200333952/|title='The Call' Dials Up WWE's Film Biz|first=Marc|last=Greaser|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 7, 2013|accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCritics were surprised by the movie's box office success because \"Berry hadn't had a hit in a number of years\" and because the R rating narrowed down the audience.<ref name=\"Goodwin\">{{cite web|url=http://filmonic.com/halle-berrys-the-call-may-get-a-sequel|title=The Call 2 \u2013 Sequel Plans|first=Liam|last=Goodwin|publisher=Filmonic|date=April 7, 2013|accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref> WWE Studios head Michael Luisi commented that ''The Call'' \"[exceeded] our most optimistic forecasts.\"<ref name=\"Goodwin\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n\nDespite mixed ratings, Berry and Breslin's performances were praised by critics and viewers alike.\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 45% based on 130 reviews, with an average rating of 5.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''The Call'' builds plenty of suspense before taking a problematic turn in the third act.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_call_2013/|title=The Call (2013)|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=June 12, 2013|year=2013}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], another film review aggregator, the film has a weighted average score of 51 out of 100, based on 23 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Call reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-call|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B rating, saying that the tale \"is surprisingly good and surprisingly gruesome fun. Eklund makes the most of the maniac role and Breslin is a sympathetic victim.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20483133_20682484,00.html |title= The Call |journal= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 15, 2013 |location= New York |publisher= Time Inc.}}</ref> Reviewer Dwight Brown wrote, \"The script gives Berry a blue-collar character she can make accessible, vulnerable and gutsy... Chestnut is not suitably gallant and stalwart as her caring lover and a cop on a mission... This film is a whole lot scarier than you think it's going to be.\"<ref name=\"Brown\" /> [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"An effectively creepy thriller about a 911 operator and a young miss in peril, ''The Call'' is a model of low-budget filmmaking.\" She praised its \"clean, clever premise\" and said that Berry's Jordan is \"an old-fashioned hero in many respects, so it's fitting that Mr. Anderson uses old-fashioned filmmaking techniques, like crosscutting, to build tension and old-school exploitation tricks like evil to justify taking the story dark and then dark and bonkers.\"<ref name=\"Dargis\">{{cite news |last= Dargis |first= Manohla |authorlink= Manohla Dargis |title= Life-Altering Plea for Help |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= March 14, 2013 |url= https://movies.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/the-call-stars-halle-berry-and-abigail-breslin.html?_r=0 |accessdate= March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA reviewer for ''[[The Hutchinson News]],'' Jake Coyle, commented, \"Director Brad Anderson... working from the simple, high-concept screenplay by Richard D'Ovidio, ably cuts between Berry's increasingly emotionally-attached Jordan Turner and Breslin's panicking Casey Welson, contrasting the fraught strategizing of Turner with the frantic police pursuit of the kidnapper.\" Coyle stated that \"''The Call'' dials up a shallow thrill ride, but one efficiently peppered with your typical 'don't go in there!' moments,\" but concluded, \"''The Call'' is a rudimentary, almost old-fashioned 90-minute escape that manages to achieve its low ambitions.\" Rating the film 2 stars out of 4, Coyle writes that once the film \"manages to build some suspense from the trunk of the car-- the clever attempts to elicit help, the dwindling cell phone battery-- its deficiencies become less forgivable once the action turns off the road.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Coyle |first= Jake |title= Review: ''The Call'' dials up a shallow thriller |work= [[The Hutchinson News]] |location= Hutchinson, Kansas |publisher= Harris Enterprises |date= March 14, 2013 |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/14/the-call-dials-up-a-shallow-thriller-_n_2877693.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRoger Moore of ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' showed mixed feelings in his review: \"Rare is the thriller that goes as completely and utterly wrong as ''The Call'' does at almost precisely the one-hour mark. Which is a crying shame, because for an hour this is a riveting, by-the-book kidnapping.\" Moore explained what he saw as the highs and lows: \"Brad Anderson turns this...serial-killer hunt...into a real edge-of-your-seat thriller. Given...a half-decent tale of horror, guilt, problem-solving and redemption, Anderson couldn't go far wrong,\" but, Moore states, \"It's only when our Oscar-winning heroine puts down the phone and sets out to do some sleuthing of her own that ''The Call'' disconnects, turning into something far more generic and far less exciting.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Moore |first= Roger |title= After a riveting hour, hang up |work= [[The Seattle Times]] |location= Seattle |publisher= Seattle Times Company |date= March 15, 2013 |url= http://seattletimes.com/avantgo/2020561052.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' turned in a similar review: \"The semi-fresh thriller, set mainly in an emergency call center and on the freeways of Los Angeles, puts a tech slant on a damsel-in-distress setup. It buzzes along for a while, the promising plot innovations inviting suspension of disbelief, before by-the-numbers implausibility, over-the-top valor and unsavory contrivances take over and the line goes dead.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Linden |first= Sheri |title= Review: Halle Berry is fierce in 'The Call,' but script needs 911 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date= March 14, 2013 |url= http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-the-call-review-20130315,0,156299.story |accessdate= March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nBerry was nominated for two awards for her role as Turner in ''The Call'' in 2013. She was nominated for Best Actress for the [[BET Awards]], which were created by the [[Black Entertainment Television]] network to celebrate [[African American]]s and other minorities in music, acting, sports and other fields of entertainment over the past year, Berry lost to [[Kerry Washington]] for the role in ''[[Django Unchained]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/overtheropes/wwestudios/halle-berry-the-call-bet-award-nomination|title=Halle Berry nominated for BET Award for \"The Call\"|publisher=[[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc]]|date=June 11, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> She was also nominated for Choice Movie Actress in a Drama at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], but lost to [[Emma Watson]] for ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allvoices.com/news/14669539-halle-berry-teen-choice-awards-nominee-for-the-call|title=Halle Berry: Teen Choice Awards Nominee for 'The Call'!|publisher=[[Just Jared]]|date=May 23, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203161059/http://www.allvoices.com/news/14669539-halle-berry-teen-choice-awards-nominee-for-the-call|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film was also nominated for Best Thriller Film at the [[40th Saturn Awards]] and Berry was nominated for [[Saturn Award for Best Actress]], but lost to ''[[World War Z (film)|World War Z]]'' and [[Sandra Bullock]], respectively.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring home invasions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{IMDb title|1911644|The Call}}\n*{{mojo title|call2013|The Call}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|the_call_2013|The Call}}\n*{{metacritic film|the-call|The Call}}\n\n{{Brad Anderson}}\n{{WWE Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Call, The}}\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Emergency communication]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films about child abduction]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brad Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Incest in film]]\n[[Category:Stage 6 Films films]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n[[Category:WWE Studios films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Call\n| image          = The Call poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Brad Anderson (director)|Brad Anderson]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|Jeff Graup|Michael Luisi|Michael A. Helfant|Robert L. Stein|Bradley Gallo}}\n| screenplay     = Richard D'Ovidio\n| story          = {{ubl|Richard D'Ovidio|Nicole D'Ovidio|[[Jon Bokenkamp]]}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Halle Berry]]|[[Abigail Breslin]]|[[Morris Chestnut]]|[[Michael Eklund]]|[[David Otunga]]|[[Michael Imperioli]]}}\n| music          = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Thomas Yatsko]]\n| editing        = Avi Youabian\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[Stage 6 Films]]|Troika Pictures|[[WWE Studios]]|Amasia Entertainment|Apotheosis Media Group}}\n| distributor    = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|03|15}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 94:15 --><ref>{{cite web|title=''THE CALL'' (15)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/call-2013-1|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130624234542/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/call-2013-1|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 24, 2013|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=June 7, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $13 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=call2013.htm |title= The Call (2013)|website= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n| gross          = $68.6 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Call''''' is a 2013 American [[psychological thriller]] [[crime film]] directed by [[Brad Anderson (director)|Brad Anderson]] and written by Richard D'Ovidio. The film stars [[Abigail Breslin]] as Casey Welson, a teenage girl kidnapped by a [[serial killer]] and [[Halle Berry]] as Jordan Turner, a [[9-1-1]] operator, still suffering emotionally from a prior botched 9-1-1 call, who receives Casey's call. [[Morris Chestnut]], [[Michael Eklund]], [[Michael Imperioli]], and [[David Otunga]] also star. The story was originally envisioned as a television series, but D'Ovidio later rewrote it as a feature film. Filming began in July 2012 and spanned a period of 25 days, with all scenes being shot in [[California]], mainly [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] and [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]].\n\nA screening of ''The Call'' was held at the Women's International Film Festival hosted at the Regal South Beach theater on February 26, 2013. [[TriStar Pictures]] released it to theatres on March 15, 2013. Considered to be [[high-concept]] by many reviewers, the film proved a commercial success, grossing over $68 million against budget of $13 million. Halle Berry was nominated for Choice Movie Actress in a Drama at the [[Teen Choice Awards]] and Best Actress at the [[BET Awards]] while the film itself received mixed reviews from critics, but praised Berry and Breslin's performances and the film's suspense.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Los Angeles Police Department]] veteran [[9-1-1]] operator, Jordan Turner, receives a call one night, from a teenage girl, Leah Templeton, fearing for her life as a man breaks into her home. Jordan calmly advises her to conceal herself upstairs. When the call is disconnected, Jordan calls Leah back, a decision that costs Leah her life. The ringing phone gives her location away to the intruder. Jordan attempts to dissuade him from going further over the phone. He responds \"It's already done\" and hangs up, leaving her distraught.\n\nThe next day, Jordan sees a television report confirming that Leah has been murdered. Emotionally affected by the incident, Jordan tells her boyfriend, Officer Paul Phillips, that she can no longer handle field calls.\n\nSix months later, she is working as a trainer for 9-1-1 operators. Teenager Casey Welson is kidnapped from a mall parking garage by a man named Michael Foster after shopping with her friend, Autumn, and forced into the trunk of his car. Casey had taken Autumn's [[TracFone|disposable phone]] after she accidentally left it in the mall, and uses it to call 9-1-1. A rookie operator, Brooke, receives the call but is unable to handle it, prompting Jordan to take over. However, Casey's use of a disposable Phase I phone means that her location cannot be determined by GPS, showing only the location of the Cell Tower the disposable is connected to.\n\nWhile Michael drives, Jordan guides Casey through knocking out a [[tail light]] and signaling people in nearby cars. One woman who sees Casey waving her arm out of the trunk of the car calls 9-1-1 on a phone with Phase II capabilities, allowing the police to narrow their search. When Casey tells Jordan that there are cans of paint in the trunk, Jordan has Casey pour the paint out of the taillight hole. This attracts the attention of another motorist, Alan Denado, but Michael knocks him out with a shovel, and assuming him to be dead stuffs Alan in the trunk with Casey.\n\nAlan reawakens in the trunk and begins screaming uncontrollably, and Michael stabs him, unfortunately Alan gives away an Escape Lever to Michael who rips it out. Michael stops at a gas station where Casey gets an idea to crawl out of the trunk and scream for help. A gas attendant attempts to bust the door open, but Michael sprays him with gasoline and throws a lighter at him.\n\nUpon arriving at his destination, Michael removes Casey from the trunk and finds the phone in her pocket, with 9-1-1 listening on the line. Through the phone, Jordan informs him that his identity is uncovered and advises him to turn himself in and not hurt the girl. Before smashing the phone, Michael responds, \"It's already done\", leading Jordan to realize that Michael is the same culprit who killed Leah six months prior.\n\nMeanwhile, Paul, accompanied by Officer Jake Devans and others in law enforcement, raid Michael's home, but find only his wife and children. Finding a photo of Michael and his sister, Melinda, they realize that Casey resembles her. Additionally, the house seen in the photo is eventually revealed by Michael's wife to have burned down, although a nearby cottage still remains. The police raid it, but find nobody there and leave.\n\nMichael begins to wash and cut Casey's hair. Determined to rescue Casey, Jordan drives to the secondary home where she finds a number of photos of Michael with his [[leukemia]]-stricken sister. Stepping outside, she recognizes sounds from an outdoor [[flagpole]]\u2014exactly the same sound she heard in the background in the final moments of the 9-1-1 call. She also finds a trap door amid dirt and scrub located where the primary house once stood. Jordan accidentally drops her cellphone down the cellar and climbs down in without calling the police.\n\nNavigating the cellar, Jordan hides from an emerging Michael. The cellar itself pieces together Michael's backstory. Michael had [[incest]]uous feelings towards his sister and was distraught when she fell ill, lost all of her hair and died of leukemia. Michael has a prop head that he keeps in the cellar that he treats like his sister. He has also been scalping and killing young girls who have similar blond hair, trying to find scalps that match his sister's hair.\n\nJordan soon finds Casey strapped down to a dentist chair and attacks Michael, as he begins to lacerate Casey's scalp. She frees Casey and both make an attempt to escape the cellar, during which Casey stabs Michael in the back with a pair of scissors. Michael pursues them and they are able to injure and kick him back down into the cellar, rendering him unconscious. While he is knocked out, they tie him to a chair.\n\nWhen he regains consciousness, they inform him that they plan to [[starvation|leave him to die]] and claim that Casey had escaped, that she was found by Jordan in the woods, and that Michael disappeared. Michael pleads that they cannot just leave him there, but Jordan replies using Michael's own words, \"It's already done.\" Michael shouts insults at them, Jordan locks the door and leaves, avenging Leah's death.\n\n==Cast==\n{{divcol}}\n* [[Halle Berry]] as Jordan Turner, a 9-1-1 operator\n* [[Abigail Breslin]] as Casey Welson, a kidnapped teenager\n* [[Morris Chestnut]] as Officer Paul Phillips, Jordan's boyfriend\n* [[Michael Eklund]] as Michael Lewis Foster, Casey's kidnapper\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as Alan Denado, Michael's victim\n* [[David Otunga]] as Officer Jake Devan\n* [[Justina Machado]] as Rachel\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Z\u00fa\u00f1iga]] as Marco\n* [[Roma Maffia]] as Maddy\n* Evie Thompson as Leah Templeton\n* Denise Dowse as Flora\n* [[Ella Rae Peck]] as Autumn\n* [[Jenna Lamia]] as Brooke\n* Ross Gallo as Josh\n* Shawnee Badger as Melinda Foster\n* [[Tara Platt]] as Female Trainee\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Writing and casting===\n{{quote box\n|width = 30em\n|border = 1px\n|align=right\n|bgcolor=#c6dbf7\n|fontsize = 85%\n|title_bg =\n|title_fnt =\n|title =\n|quote = \"I thought, 'That's a world we've never seen before in a film.' You never get to see the other side of it. [They were playing some actual calls on the news segment, and] listening to the calls, I got a chill up my spine as I envisioned what was going on [on the other end of the phone], and I thought that it would be a great world to play into.\"\n|salign = right\n|source =\u2014Screenwriter Richard D'Ovidio on the radio segment that led him to write the screenplay for ''The Call''<ref name= \"Decker\" />\n}}\nScreenwriter Richard D'Ovidio was inspired to script the story after his wife heard an NPR segment with a 9-1-1 operator discussing her job. He began to research the subject and visited the Los Angeles Metropolitan Communications Dispatch Center (MCDC). Finding the center, which has backup generators, bulletproof windows, and a moat surrounding the building, to be \"pretty amazing,\" he decided to shed light on what he viewed as a previously overlooked occupation. The story was originally conceptualized as a television series titled ''The Hive'' (a reference to the constant calls and conversations sounding like bees buzzing), but D'Ovidio decided to redraft it as a film on realizing that \"the operators couldn't be the ones kicking in doors and going out into the field\" all the time. As a result, what was planned to be the pilot episode was expanded and revised as a movie.<ref name=\"Decker\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/62781/call-set-visit-report-part-one-writer-richard-dovidio-his-inspiration-research-and-more |author= Decker, Sean |date= January 14, 2013 |title= The Call Set Visit Report - Part One: Writer Richard D'Ovidio on His Inspiration, Research, and More! |publisher= Dread Central |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dwight-brown/the-call_b_2875451.html?ir=Entertainment |author= Brown, Dwight |date= March 15, 2013 |title= The Call |work= [[The Huffington Post]] |quote= Jordan (Berry) works in the L.A. 911 call center. They call it the hive, because with the constant din of conversations it sounds like bees at work. |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor most of the film, Berry's character, Turner, the 9-1-1 operator, does stay inside \"the hive\" before becoming actively involved in the search for Breslin's character, Welson, the kidnapped caller. D'Ovidio chose two female leads, explaining, \"I wanted strong women... I think it was appropriate here, since most 911 call operators are women.\"<ref name=\"Decker\" /> Berry remarked, \"I love the idea of being a part of a movie that was so empowering for women. We don't often get to play roles like this, where ordinary people become heroic and do something extraordinary.\"<ref name=\"Grant\">{{cite news |last= Grant |first= Kimberly |title= Berry, Chestnut Expound on ''The Call'' Roles - and more |work= South Florida Times |location= Fort Lauderdale |date= March 13, 2013 |url= http://www.sfltimes.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12684&Itemid=187 |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> D'Ovidio chose to tell the story from the perspective of two characters\u2014the operator and the caller\u2014believing that it would become repetitive if it focused on only one. As a result, he switched perspectives every ten pages when writing the screenplay. As well as collaborating on the story with his wife, Nicole and Jon Bokenkamp, he accepted suggestions from Berry, Breslin and Eklund: \"Halle came in with some great notes and Abigail and Michael and it started to flesh things out. I'm not one to say 'no' to a great suggested line of dialogue. It just makes me look better as a writer! I feel it's a very collaborative process, and some of the happiest accidents happen when you just listen to people. When someone comes up to you and says, 'Why don't we do it this way?' I think that it's important to listen.\"<ref name=\"Decker\" />\n\nChestnut, who plays Phillips, a police officer and Turner's boyfriend, prepared by riding along with Los Angeles police officers to observe what it is like to be an officer in a squad car<ref name=\"Grant\" /> and Berry prepared for the role by visiting a call center and observing the operators at work.<ref name=\"Decker\" /> She told a ''[[The Miami Herald|Miami Herald]]'' interviewer, \"You get a different perspective by doing research... You can't know what it's like to be a cop even though you've seen it in the movies. But nobody ever saw a 9-1-1 center. I thought they lived in the ground somewhere! It was interesting to see who they were and how they deal and how stressful it can be. I was a wreck watching them. They would just be as cool as can be doing their thing. I thought, 'I could never do this job.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Marr |first= Madeleine |title= Call 911! It's Halle Berry and Morris Chestnut |work= [[The Miami Herald]] |location= Miami |publisher= The McClatchy Company |date= March 10, 2013 |url= http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/03/10/3274730/call-911-its-halle-berry-and-morris.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nProducers scheduled for ''The Call'' to be filmed in Canada in June 2011 after they failed to make the cut for a California tax credit. With a low budget of $13 million, they settled on [[Ottawa, Ontario]], where director Anderson had just finished another project. However, the [[California Film Commission]] (CFC) called back nine months later and informed them that the waiting list had been largely cleared and that they now qualified for $1.9 million in tax deduction. According to Producer Michael Helfant, they were \"literally days from starting to put down a deposit.\" Berry was reportedly pleased with the news, having wanted to stay in Los Angeles and the CFC helped secure film locations for the project.<ref name=\"Verrier\">{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Verrier|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/mar/20/business/la-fi-ct-onlocation-20130320|title=A Fateful Call Keeps Filming of 'The Call' in L.A.|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWith a crew of roughly 120 persons, filming took a total of 25 days, spanning from July to August 2012. Car chase scenes were shot at [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] and a [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]] office building was modeled as the emergency dispatch center. The latter was also used for the scenes in which Welson is locked in the trunk of a car. Other filming locations include the [[Burbank Town Center]] on Magnolia Boulevard in [[Burbank, California]], [[Santa Clarita, California]] and the 170 Highway.<ref name=\"Verrier\" /> At one point, Berry was rushed to [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]] after falling headfirst on concrete while shooting a fight sequence. A spokesperson for Berry confirmed that she suffered a minor head injury and was taken to the hospital as a precaution, but she checked out healthy and was released.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2175149/Halle-Berry-rushed-hospital-accident-movie-set.html |title=Pictured: Halle Berry rushed to hospital 'after accident on movie set' |first=Sarah |last=Bull |work=[[Daily Mail]] |location=London |date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBerry told interviewer Kimberly Grant, \"The hard part for me was to try to stay connected to Phillips and Welson.\" This was because, Grant writes, \"she had to spend an entire day reading 21 pages of dialogue, rattling off in quick succession 911-operator jargon, that would be cut and edited to fit the film... In film terms, that means Berry performed for 21 minutes straight with no breaks, not an easy feat for any actor.\" Though she enjoyed working with Chestnut,<ref name=\"Zwecker\" /> Berry told Grant that it was difficult being unable to see her co-stars for most of the film: \"That was my constant challenge; to stay on such an emotional level [as Jordan], so that I would be on the same level as they [i.e., Casey and Officer Phillips] were. I used that feeling of frustration and of being stuck to fuel my character.\"<ref name=\"Grant\" />\n\n===Music===\nThe score of the film is composed by John Debney. Unlike the other films he composed with an orchestra, the film's score is completely filled with dark and intense electronic and synthesized elements. Although, he used little orchestral elements in the score.\n\n==Promotion and release==\n\n[[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] paid very little money to acquire U.S. distribution rights.<ref>https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120629005601/en/WWE-Studios-Enters-Hive-Troika-Pictures</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite journal |url= http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/03/16/friday-box-office-oz-the-call-burt-wonderstone/ |last= Smith |first= Grady |title= Box office update: ''Oz'' wins Friday with $11.4 million; ''The Call'' crushes ''Burt Wonderstone'' |journal= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 16, 2013 |location= New York |publisher= Time Inc. |page= }}</ref> But the film screened for a test audience in November 2012 and scores were even higher than anticipated, prompting Sony to give the film a wide theatrical release.<ref>https://variety.com/2013/film/news/sony-shuffles-carrie-the-call-1118064130/</ref>\n\nSpanning 94 minutes upon completion, the movie received an R rating for violence, disturbing content and some language.<ref name=\"Dargis\" /> Berry and Chestnut promoted the film at the ShowPlace ICON movie theater<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theybf.com/2013/03/01/getting-an-eyeful-morris-chestnut-halle-berry-roll-to-chicago-to-promote-the-call|author=Natasha|date=March 1, 2013|title= GETTING AN EYEFUL: Morris Chestnut & Halle Berry Roll To Chicago To Promote ''The Call''|publisher=[[Theybf.com]]|accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> at the red-carpet premiere in Chicago on February 28.<ref name=\"Zwecker\">{{cite news|last=Zwecker|first=Bill|title=Halle Berry says 'I was the lucky one' in Morris Chestnut love scenes|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=Chicago|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|date= March 12, 2013|url= http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/18808973-421/halle-berry-says-i-was-the-lucky-one-in-morris-chestnut-love-scenes.html|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> Berry also traveled to Rio to promote ''The Call'' in anticipation of its April 12 release in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news|title=Halle Berry Announces Brazilian Visit to Promote 'The Call'|work=Boxoffice|date= March 28, 2013|url=http://www.boxoffice.com/latest-news/2013-03-28-halle-berry-announces-brazilian-visit-to-promote-the-call|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Women's International Film Festival hosted a screening of ''The Call'' at the Regal South Beach theater on February 26, 2013.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://oceandrive.com/events |last= Caballero |first= Gustavo |title= Events / 'The Call' Red Carpet Screening |journal= Ocean Drive |location= Miami Beach, FL |publisher= |date= February 26, 2013 |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> Chestnut told the audience that he would sign on for a sequel, saying about Berry, \"I didn't get to kiss this woman enough!\" Berry added, \"I'm in the movie and even I was scared.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Marr|first=Madeleine|title=Will Matt Damon renew vows in Miami?|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|location=Miami|publisher=The McClatchy Company|date=February 28, 2013|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/02/28/3259330/will-matt-damon-renew-vows-in.html|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> The film was released in theatres on March 15 and on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc]] on June 25 of that same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Call|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Call-Blu-ray/70091/|publisher=[[Blu-ray]]|date=June 25, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> DVD extras included a [[featurette]] entitled \"Emergency Procedure: Making the Film\" and commentary from Abigail Breslin, Halle Berry, and other filmmakers. The Blu-ray version came with more features, including [[deleted scene]]s, an alternate ending, Michael Eklund's audition tape, featurettes entitled \"A Set Tour of The Hive and The Lair\" and \"Inside the Stunts\", as well as all of the original DVD content.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rawden|first=Jessica|title=The Call Will Hit Blu-ray And DVD In June|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Call-Hit-Blu-ray-DVD-June-37405.html|publisher=Cinema Blend|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n\nAccording to ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|Boxoffice]],'' ''The Call'' was expected to earn about $11\u201312 million on its opening weekend in 2,507 theaters across the United States but surpassed this by a significant margin and grossed $17 million in its first three days. This indicated good profits, as the film cost about $13 million to produce and Sony paid a much smaller amount to acquire U.S. distribution rights.<ref name=\"Smith\"/> With box office takings of over $68 million, ''The Call'' is [[WWE Studios]]' most commercially successful film to date, the previous top-grossing productions being ''[[See No Evil (2006 film)|See No Evil]],'' which stars [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] (Glenn Jacobs) ($19 million) and ''[[12 Rounds (film)|12 Rounds]],'' which stars [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[John Cena]] ($17 million).<ref name=\"Greaser\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/the-call-dials-up-wwes-film-biz-1200333952/|title='The Call' Dials Up WWE's Film Biz|first=Marc|last=Greaser|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 7, 2013|accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCritics were surprised by the movie's box office success because \"Berry hadn't had a hit in a number of years\" and because the R rating narrowed down the audience.<ref name=\"Goodwin\">{{cite web|url=http://filmonic.com/halle-berrys-the-call-may-get-a-sequel|title=The Call 2 \u2013 Sequel Plans|first=Liam|last=Goodwin|publisher=Filmonic|date=April 7, 2013|accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref> WWE Studios head Michael Luisi commented that ''The Call'' \"[exceeded] our most optimistic forecasts.\"<ref name=\"Goodwin\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n\nDespite mixed ratings, Berry and Breslin's performances were praised by critics and viewers alike.\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 45% based on 130 reviews, with an average rating of 5.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''The Call'' builds plenty of suspense before taking a problematic turn in the third act.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_call_2013/|title=The Call (2013)|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=June 12, 2013|year=2013}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], another film review aggregator, the film has a weighted average score of 51 out of 100, based on 23 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Call reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-call|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B rating, saying that the tale \"is surprisingly good and surprisingly gruesome fun. Eklund makes the most of the maniac role and Breslin is a sympathetic victim.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20483133_20682484,00.html |title= The Call |journal= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 15, 2013 |location= New York |publisher= Time Inc.}}</ref> Reviewer Dwight Brown wrote, \"The script gives Berry a blue-collar character she can make accessible, vulnerable and gutsy... Chestnut is not suitably gallant and stalwart as her caring lover and a cop on a mission... This film is a whole lot scarier than you think it's going to be.\"<ref name=\"Brown\" /> [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"An effectively creepy thriller about a 911 operator and a young miss in peril, ''The Call'' is a model of low-budget filmmaking.\" She praised its \"clean, clever premise\" and said that Berry's Jordan is \"an old-fashioned hero in many respects, so it's fitting that Mr. Anderson uses old-fashioned filmmaking techniques, like crosscutting, to build tension and old-school exploitation tricks like evil to justify taking the story dark and then dark and bonkers.\"<ref name=\"Dargis\">{{cite news |last= Dargis |first= Manohla |authorlink= Manohla Dargis |title= Life-Altering Plea for Help |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= March 14, 2013 |url= https://movies.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/the-call-stars-halle-berry-and-abigail-breslin.html?_r=0 |accessdate= March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA reviewer for ''[[The Hutchinson News]],'' Jake Coyle, commented, \"Director Brad Anderson... working from the simple, high-concept screenplay by Richard D'Ovidio, ably cuts between Berry's increasingly emotionally-attached Jordan Turner and Breslin's panicking Casey Welson, contrasting the fraught strategizing of Turner with the frantic police pursuit of the kidnapper.\" Coyle stated that \"''The Call'' dials up a shallow thrill ride, but one efficiently peppered with your typical 'don't go in there!' moments,\" but concluded, \"''The Call'' is a rudimentary, almost old-fashioned 90-minute escape that manages to achieve its low ambitions.\" Rating the film 2 stars out of 4, Coyle writes that once the film \"manages to build some suspense from the trunk of the car-- the clever attempts to elicit help, the dwindling cell phone battery-- its deficiencies become less forgivable once the action turns off the road.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Coyle |first= Jake |title= Review: ''The Call'' dials up a shallow thriller |work= [[The Hutchinson News]] |location= Hutchinson, Kansas |publisher= Harris Enterprises |date= March 14, 2013 |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/14/the-call-dials-up-a-shallow-thriller-_n_2877693.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRoger Moore of ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' showed mixed feelings in his review: \"Rare is the thriller that goes as completely and utterly wrong as ''The Call'' does at almost precisely the one-hour mark. Which is a crying shame, because for an hour this is a riveting, by-the-book kidnapping.\" Moore explained what he saw as the highs and lows: \"Brad Anderson turns this...serial-killer hunt...into a real edge-of-your-seat thriller. Given...a half-decent tale of horror, guilt, problem-solving and redemption, Anderson couldn't go far wrong,\" but, Moore states, \"It's only when our Oscar-winning heroine puts down the phone and sets out to do some sleuthing of her own that ''The Call'' disconnects, turning into something far more generic and far less exciting.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Moore |first= Roger |title= After a riveting hour, hang up |work= [[The Seattle Times]] |location= Seattle |publisher= Seattle Times Company |date= March 15, 2013 |url= http://seattletimes.com/avantgo/2020561052.html |accessdate= March 17, 2013}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' turned in a similar review: \"The semi-fresh thriller, set mainly in an emergency call center and on the freeways of Los Angeles, puts a tech slant on a damsel-in-distress setup. It buzzes along for a while, the promising plot innovations inviting suspension of disbelief, before by-the-numbers implausibility, over-the-top valor and unsavory contrivances take over and the line goes dead.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Linden |first= Sheri |title= Review: Halle Berry is fierce in 'The Call,' but script needs 911 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date= March 14, 2013 |url= http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-the-call-review-20130315,0,156299.story |accessdate= March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nBerry was nominated for two awards for her role as Turner in ''The Call'' in 2013. She was nominated for Best Actress for the [[BET Awards]], which were created by the [[Black Entertainment Television]] network to celebrate [[African American]]s and other minorities in music, acting, sports and other fields of entertainment over the past year, Berry lost to [[Kerry Washington]] for the role in ''[[Django Unchained]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/overtheropes/wwestudios/halle-berry-the-call-bet-award-nomination|title=Halle Berry nominated for BET Award for \"The Call\"|publisher=[[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc]]|date=June 11, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> She was also nominated for Choice Movie Actress in a Drama at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], but lost to [[Emma Watson]] for ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allvoices.com/news/14669539-halle-berry-teen-choice-awards-nominee-for-the-call|title=Halle Berry: Teen Choice Awards Nominee for 'The Call'!|publisher=[[Just Jared]]|date=May 23, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203161059/http://www.allvoices.com/news/14669539-halle-berry-teen-choice-awards-nominee-for-the-call|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film was also nominated for Best Thriller Film at the [[40th Saturn Awards]] and Berry was nominated for [[Saturn Award for Best Actress]], but lost to ''[[World War Z (film)|World War Z]]'' and [[Sandra Bullock]], respectively.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring home invasions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{IMDb title|1911644|The Call}}\n*{{mojo title|call2013|The Call}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|the_call_2013|The Call}}\n*{{metacritic film|the-call|The Call}}\n\n{{Brad Anderson}}\n{{WWE Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Call, The}}\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Emergency communication]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films about child abduction]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brad Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Incest in film]]\n[[Category:Stage 6 Films films]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n[[Category:WWE Studios films]]\n", "name_user": "Oliver Wendell 2009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Call_(2013_film)"}
{"title_page": "M-28 (Michigan highway)", "text_new": "{{short description|Highway in Michigan, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MI\n|type=M\n|route=28\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=240|frame-lat=46.455|frame-long=-87.144|zoom=6|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/M-28 (Michigan highway)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=M-28 highlighted in red\n|map_alt=A map of the Upper Peninsula of Michigan showing M-28 in red crossing east\u2013west, intersecting an Interstate on the east end\n|length_mi=290.373\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"PRFA\"/>\n|established={{circa|July 1, 1919}}<ref name=\"MSHD19\"/>\n|tourist=[[File:Lake Superior Circle Tour.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] [[Lake Superior Circle Tour]]\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MI|US|2}} at [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|45}} at [[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|141}} near [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|41}} in [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]] \n*{{jct|state=MI|M|35}} near [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|41}} in [[Harvey, Michigan|Harvey]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|75}} near [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]]\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MI|M|129}} near [[Sault Ste Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]\n|counties=[[Gogebic County, Michigan|Gogebic]], [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon]], [[Houghton County, Michigan|Houghton]], [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga]], [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette]], [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger]], [[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft]], [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce]], [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa]]\n|previous_type=M\n|previous_route=27\n|next_type=M\n|next_route=29\n|browse={{mi browse|previous_type=M 1926|previous_route=177|route={{nowrap|M-178}}|next_type=M|next_route=179}}\n\n}}\n\n'''M-28''' is an east\u2013west [[Michigan Highway System|state trunkline highway]] that traverses nearly all of the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper Peninsula]] of the U.S. state of [[Michigan]], from [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]] to near [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]] in [[Bruce Township, Chippewa County, Michigan|Bruce Township]]. Along with [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US Highway 2]] (US&nbsp;2), M-28 forms a pair of primary highways linking the Upper Peninsula from end to end, providing a major access route for traffic from Michigan and Canada along the southern shore of [[Lake Superior]]. M-28 is the longest state trunkline in Michigan numbered with the \"M-\" prefix at {{convert|290.373|mi|km|3}}. The entire highway is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], while three sections of M-28 are part of the [[Lake Superior Circle Tour]]. M-28 also carries two memorial highway designations along its route.\n\nThroughout its course across the Upper Peninsula, M-28 passes through forested woodlands, bog swamps, urbanized areas, and along the Lake Superior shoreline. Sections of roadway cross the [[Ottawa National Forest]] and both units of the [[Hiawatha National Forest]]. Some of the other landmarks accessible from M-28 include the Seney Stretch, [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]] and several historic bridges.\n\nM-28 is an original trunkline designation, dating to the 1919 formation of the state's trunkline system. The original highway was much shorter than the current version. M-28 was expanded eastward to the Sault Ste. Marie area in the late 1920s. The western end has been expanded twice to different locations on the [[Wisconsin]] state line. Other changes along the routing have led to the creation of three different [[business loop]]s at various times, with one still extant. Future changes, proposed by Marquette County but not accepted by the [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT), could see M-28 rerouted over County Road&nbsp;480 (CR&nbsp;480).\n\n== Route description ==\n[[File:M-28 Trout Creek.jpg|thumb|left|Clouds brewing over M-28 in western Ontonagon County|alt=a highway curving over the crest of a hill flanked by telephone poles on either side. There is a white road sign on the right side of the road and storm clouds in the sky.]]\nM-28 is a major highway for Michigan and Canadian traffic along the south shore of Lake Superior. It forms the northern half of a pair of primary trunklines linking the Upper Peninsula from end to end; [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] is the southern partner.<ref name=\"MDOT2\"/> The {{convert| 290.373|mi|km|adj=on}} highway comprises mostly two lanes, undivided except for sections that are [[Concurrency (road)|concurrent]] with [[U.S. Route 41 in Michigan|US&nbsp;41]] near [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]]. The \"Marquette Bypass\" portion of US&nbsp;41/M-28 is a four-lane [[Limited-access road|expressway]], and segments of the highway in [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] have four lanes.<ref name=\"MDOT14\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 2014 |sections= C1\u2013C11 }}</ref> The entire route is part of the National Highway System,<ref name=\"NHS\">{{cite map |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = National Highway System, Michigan |date = April 23, 2006 |location = Lansing |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |format = PDF |scale = Scale not given |access-date = February 4, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/6AqxSurw0?url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |archivedate = September 21, 2012 |df = }}</ref> and three sections of the trunkline are part of the Lake Superior Circle Tour.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n=== Western terminus to Shingleton ===\nIn the west, M-28 begins at a signalized intersection with US&nbsp;2 in Wakefield. Heading north, the highway passes Sunday Lake heading out of town. After crossing into southwestern [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]] and the [[Eastern Time Zone]], the trunkline highway skirts the northern shore of [[Lake Gogebic]], running concurrently with [[M-64 (Michigan highway)|M-64]]. The first section of M-28 designated as a part of the Lake Superior Circle Tour is from the western terminus to the eastern junction with M-64 in [[Bergland, Michigan|Bergland]], where the Circle Tour turns north along M-64, leaving M-28. Here, M-28 has its lowest traffic counts; within the 2013 MDOT survey, the road is listed with only an [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT) of 1,425 vehicles on a section of highway between Bergland and the [[U.S. Route 45 in Michigan|US&nbsp;45]] intersection in [[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]].<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author = Bureau of Transportation Planning |url = http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title = Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |year = 2008 |access-date = December 19, 2014 }}</ref> The trunkline runs through heavily forested areas of southern [[Houghton County, Michigan|Houghton]] and [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga counties]]. At the eastern junction with US&nbsp;41 near Covington, M-28 receives the Circle Tour designation again<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/> and exits the [[Ottawa National Forest]].<ref name=\"RM13\">{{cite map |author = [[Rand McNally]] |title = The Road Atlas |map = Michigan |edition = 2013 Walmart |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally |year = 2013 |scale = 1:1,267,200 and 1:1900,800 |sections = C10\u2013C14, D1\u2013D9 |pages = 50\u201351 |isbn = 0-528-00626-6 |oclc = 773666955 }}</ref>\n\nIn Baraga and Marquette counties, US&nbsp;41/M-28 passes through hilly terrain before entering the urban areas of [[Ishpeming, Michigan|Ishpeming]], [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]] and Marquette.<ref name=\"MDOT2\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = Chapter One: Introduction |work = US&nbsp;41/M-28 Access Management Plan |date = April 28, 2004 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_US-41_M28_chapter1_108596_7.pdf |access-date = January 18, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071223031233/http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_US-41_M28_chapter1_108596_7.pdf |archivedate = December 23, 2007 }}</ref> Approximately 13,000\u201317,000&nbsp;vehicles use this section from Ishpeming eastward through Negaunee. West of the city of Marquette, US&nbsp;41/M-28 had a peak 2013 AADT of 32,805&nbsp;vehicles in [[Marquette Township, Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette Township]] along a retail and business corridor. This peak level is sustained until the start of the Marquette Bypass, where the traffic returns to the 16,500-vehicle and higher levels seen in Ishpeming and Negaunee. South of the city of Marquette, traffic counts once again climb to 19,620&nbsp;vehicles. In [[Chocolay Township, Michigan|Chocolay Township]] the AADT drops to 8,840&nbsp;vehicles before tapering off to 3,065&nbsp;vehicles by the county line.<ref name=\"TMIS\"/>\n\nAt the Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee city line, M-28 changes memorial highway designations. From the western terminus to this point, M-28 is called the \"Veterans Memorial Highway\", but it becomes the \"D. J. Jacobetti Memorial Highway\" to honor the longest-serving member of the [[Michigan Legislature]], [[Dominic Jacobetti|Dominic J. Jacobetti]].<ref name=\"memorial\">{{cite book |last = Barnett |first = LeRoy |year = 2004 |title = A Drive Down Memory Lane: The Named State and Federal Highways of Michigan |location = Allegan Forest, Michigan |publisher = Priscilla Press |pages = 115\u201316, 226 |isbn = 1-886167-24-9 |oclc = 57425393 }}</ref><ref name=\"jacobetti\">{{cite news |last = Prusi |first = Renee |title = End of an Era: Jacobetti Dies This Morning |date = November 28, 1994 |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |location = Marquette, Michigan |pages = 1A, 5A |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> The Jacobetti Highway designation ends at the eastern M-123 junction in [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]].<ref name=\"PA142\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Legislature |title = Michigan Memorial Highway Act (PA 142 of 2001) |url = http://legislature.mi.gov/doc.aspx?mcl-Act-142-of-2001 |date = October 26, 2001 |access-date = June 6, 2008 |author-link = Michigan Legislature }}</ref>\n[[File:Hiawatha National Forest.jpg|right|thumb|[[Hiawatha National Forest]] road sign on M-28/[[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] in [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]] west of [[Shingleton, Michigan|Shingleton]]|alt=A brown and white wooden sign for the Hiawatha National Forest mounted on a stone base. The sign is installed on the right side of a highway between the road and the forest on the far right.]]\n\nBetween Marquette and [[Munising, Michigan|Munising]], M-28 closely parallels the Lake Superior shoreline, providing scenic views of the lake and its \"lonesome sandy beaches\".<ref name=\"huntsPR\">{{cite book |last1 = Hunt |first1 = Mary |last2 = Hunt |first2 = Don |year = 2007 |title = Hunts' Guide to Michigan's Upper Peninsula |publisher = Midwestern Guides |location = Albion, Michigan |chapter-url = http://hunts-upguide.com/munising_pictured_rocks_national_lakeshore.html |chapter = Munising\u2014Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore |url = http://hunts-upguide.com/ |access-date = July 22, 2008 |last-author-amp = y }}</ref><ref name=\"fowler\">{{cite news |last = Fowler |first = Brenda |title = Endless Trails To Open Water |url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05EEDD1F3EF93AA15755C0A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = June 29, 1997 |access-date = February 20, 2008 |issn = 0362-4331 |oclc = 1645522 }}</ref> The Lakenenland Sculpture Park is located in [[Chocolay Township, Michigan|Chocolay Township]] near Shot Point in eastern Marquette County. This roadside attraction is owned by Tom Lakenen and features fanciful works of art made of scrap iron.<ref name=\"huntsL\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/marquette_lakenenland.html \"Lakenenland\"].}}</ref> Near the community of [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]], M-28 crosses into the western unit of the [[Hiawatha National Forest]].<ref name=\"RM13\"/> West of Munising is a ferry dock offering transport to the [[Grand Island National Recreation Area]], and at Munising there is easy access to [[Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore]]. The roadway also features [[variable-message sign]]s to warn motorists of winter weather-related traffic closures along the lakeshore. Installed at the US&nbsp;41 and [[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] junctions, the signs advise motorists which sections of roadway are closed. Per MDOT policy, only [[Winter service vehicle|snowplows]] are allowed on these sections during a closure.<ref name=\"MDOT3\">{{cite press release |first = Dawn |last = Garner |title = MDOT and MSP Prepare for Bad Weather on M-28 |date = November 23, 2005 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-130826--,00.html |access-date = January 19, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224094924/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-130826--,00.html |archivedate = December 24, 2007 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The highway exits the Hiawatha National Forest at the [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]]\u2013[[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft County]] line along the Seney Stretch.<ref name=\"RM13\"/>\n\n=== Seney Stretch ===\n[[File:seney Stretch1.jpg|thumb|left|The Seney Stretch along M-28|alt=A straight roadway leading away to the horizon with trees on either side of the road]]\nThe portion of M-28 between [[Seney, Michigan|Seney]] and [[Shingleton, Michigan|Shingleton]], called the Seney Stretch, is {{convert|25|mi|km|0}}<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&hl=en&saddr=Shingleton,+mi&daddr=Seney,+mi&ie=UTF8&z=10&om=1 |title= Overview Map of the Seney Stretch |access-date= September 15, 2006 }}</ref> of \"straight-as-an-arrow highway\"<ref name=\"Dennis\">*{{cite book |last = Dennis |first = Jerry |title = The River Home: An Angler's Explorations |publisher = St Martin's Press |date = June 1998 |isbn = 0-312-18594-4 |oclc = 38438636 |edition = 1st |location = New York |at = n.p. }}</ref> across the [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge|Great Manistique Swamp]], \"though others claim it's {{convert|50|mi|km|disp=x| [|]}}, only because it seems longer.\"<ref name=\"Spalding\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Spalding |title= You Haven't Lived Here Until... You've Driven the Seney Stretch |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] |date=August 26, 2006 |page=4A |issn= 1055-2758 |id= {{oclc| 10345127| 137343179}} }}</ref> The Seney Stretch is the longest such section of highway in the state, and \"one of the longest stretches of curveless highway east of the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]].\"<ref name=\"Carter\">*{{cite book |title = A Historical Guide to the Seney Stretch |first = James L. |last = Carter |year = 2004 |publisher = Pilot Press |location = Marquette, Michigan |oclc = 57178325 |page = 1 }}</ref> The highway is often cited as the \"state's most boring route\" according to the Michigan Economic Development Corporation (MEDC) and ''Hunts' Guide''.<ref name=\"MEDC\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Economic Development Corporation |title = Michigan Fall Color Tours: Munising, Newberry, Grand Marais |year = 2006 |work = Pure Michigan Travel |publisher = Michigan Economic Development Corporation |url = http://www.michigan.org/travel/drivingtours/detail.asp?cid=07E9B11E-0EE0-4F08-B88D-7DA087A490D6&da=y&m=9;1 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061221021805/http://www.michigan.org/travel/drivingtours/detail.asp?cid=07E9B11E-0EE0-4F08-B88D-7DA087A490D6&da=y&m=9%3B1 |archivedate = December 21, 2006 |access-date = July 22, 2008 |url-status = dead |df =  |author-link = Michigan Economic Development Corporation }}</ref><ref name=\"huntsSS\"/> The straightness and flatness over a great distance are given as reasons for the reputation of this stretch as boring.<ref name=\"huntsSS\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/shingleton.html \"Shingleton\"].}}</ref>\n\nThe road across the swamp was constructed parallel to the line of the [[Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway]] (later the [[Soo Line Railroad]]). It was first numbered as a part of [[M-25 (Michigan highway)|M-25]] when that designation was used along today's M-28 east of US&nbsp;41. The most significant changes made to the stretch since its original construction were the addition of [[Passing lane|passing relief lanes]] and a full-scale, year-round [[rest area]] in 1999.<ref name=\"mdot\">{{cite press release |first = Bill |last = Shreck |title = New Seney Rest Area Brings Year 'Round Relief to M-28 in the Upper Peninsula |date = May 28, 1999 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-95119--,00.html |access-date = September 15, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070315042130/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0%2C1607%2C7-151-9620_11057-95119--%2C00.html |archivedate = March 15, 2007 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref>\n\nPart of the Seney Stretch forms the northern border of the [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref name=\"SNWRV\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = Visitor Information |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/VisInfo.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080522073254/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/VisInfo.htm |archivedate = May 22, 2008 |date = August 15, 2007 |access-date = July 22, 2008 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |author-link = United States Fish and Wildlife Service }}</ref>  Established in 1935, this refuge is a managed [[wetland]] in [[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft County]].<ref name=\"Rosentreter\">{{cite journal |ref = Rosentreter |last = Rosentreter |first = Roger L. |title = Roosevelt's Tree Army: Michigan's Civilian Conservation Corps |date = May\u2013June 1986 |journal = [[Michigan History magazine|Michigan History]] |url = http://www.michigan.gov/hal/0,1607,7-160-17451_18670_18793-53515--,00.html |access-date = December 3, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071101015836/http://www.michigan.gov/hal/0%2C1607%2C7-160-17451_18670_18793-53515--%2C00.html |location = Lansing |publisher = [[Michigan Department of State]] |issn = 0026-2196 |oclc = 1757361 |archivedate = November 1, 2007 |url-status = dead |df = }}\n</ref> It has an area of {{convert|95212|acre|km2|0}},<ref name=\"SNWRFS\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = Fact Sheet |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/factsheet.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229130419/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/factsheet.htm |archivedate = February 29, 2008 |date = August 17, 2007 |access-date = March 18, 2008 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service }}</ref> and contains the Strangmoor Bog [[National Natural Landmark]] within its boundaries.<ref name=\"FWS\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = About Us |date = February 3, 2011 |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/about_us.html |access-date = February 23, 2011 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110320093458/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/about_us.html |archivedate = March 20, 2011 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Seney to eastern terminus ===\n[[File:M-28 McMillan.jpg|thumb|right|A passing lane on M-28 westbound near McMillan|alt=A roadway curving down a slight incline and around a bend. On the side of the road are a series of sign posts with the M-28 reassurance marker, a yellow diamond with arrows indicating the traffic directions and a yellow diamond with an arrow warning of the curve in the road.]]\nPast Seney, M-28 once again enters woodlands on the eastern end of the Upper Peninsula. In [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce County]], the roadway passes through the community of [[McMillan Township, Luce County, Michigan|McMillan]] en route to [[Newberry, Michigan|Newberry]]. The Circle Tour departs M-28 to follow [[M-123 (Michigan highway)|M-123]] at Newberry, looping north to the [[Tahquamenon Falls State Park]]. East of town, the road passes Luce County Airport off of Luce CR&nbsp;399. From there, M-28 crosses the east and west branches of the Sage River and passes south of [[McMillan Township, Luce County, Michigan|Soo Junction]], before the [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] border.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\nIn Chippewa County, M-28 begins bending slightly east-northeastward. Hulbert Lake is located south of [[Hulbert, Michigan|Hulbert]]; north of the lake, the highway enters the eastern unit of the Hiawatha National Forest.<ref name=\"RM13\"/> At the eastern junction of M-28 and M-123 near [[Eckerman, Michigan|Eckerman]] and [[Strongs, Michigan|Strongs]], the Circle Tour returns to M-28 and the D.J. Jacobetti Memorial Highway designation ends. The highway leaves the eastern unit of the Hiawatha National Forest between the communities of [[Raco, Michigan|Raco]] and [[Brimley, Michigan|Brimley]].<ref name=\"RM13\"/> [[M-221 (Michigan highway)|M-221]] leads north from the main highway on an old routing of M-28 to connect to the community of Brimley and the [[Bay Mills Indian Community]]. [[Brimley State Park]] is just east of Brimley on the old 6&nbsp;Mile&nbsp;Road alignment of M-28.<ref name=\"BSP\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Natural Resources |title = Brimley State Park Detail |url = http://www.michigandnr.com/parksandtrails/details.aspx?id=414&type=SPRK |publisher = Michigan Department of Natural Resources |access-date = March 18, 2008 }}</ref> The highway meets [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|Interstate&nbsp;75]] (I-75) at exit 386, and the Lake Superior Circle Tour departs M-28 to follow I-75. This interchange is just west of [[H-63 (Michigan county highway)|H-63]]/[[Mackinac Trail]], a former segment of US&nbsp;2. M-28 continues {{convert|3|mi|km|spell=in}} farther to its eastern terminus with [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]].<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n=== Services ===\n[[File:Scott Falls.jpg|thumb|left|Scott Falls next to a roadside park near [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]]|alt=A rock outcropping overhanging a small pool of water with a waterfall cascading into the pool]]\nAlong the routing of M-28, MDOT has established several roadside parks and rest areas. Two of these are in Ontonagon County near [[Ewen, Michigan|Ewen]] and [[Trout Creek, Michigan|Trout Creek]].<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/> A park with a picnic area and a footbridge lies near Tioga Creek in [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga County]] east of the US&nbsp;41 junction.<ref name=\"huntsTC\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/michigamme_tioga_river_roadside_park_and_waterfall.html \"Tioga River Roadside Park and Waterfall\"].}}</ref> In [[Michigamme, Michigan|Michigamme]] a scenic turnout and a roadside park overlook [[Lake Michigamme]], and along Lake Superior south of Marquette is a tourist information center built as a log cabin. East of the [[H-01 (Michigan county highway)|H-01]] junction in [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]] is a roadside park that includes [[Scott Falls]].<ref name=\"huntsSF\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/au_train_scott_falls__the_face_in_the_rock_m_dot_harold_rathfoot_roadside_park.html \"Au Train\u2014Scott Falls, The Face in the Rock, MDOT Harold Rathfoot Roadside Park\"].}}</ref> Further east, a year-round rest area is located on the western end of the Seney Stretch. Three other roadside parks lie east of Harvey in [[Shelter Bay, Michigan|Shelter Bay]], on the shores of Deer Lake and west of Newberry.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Mainline history ===\nFormed by July 1, 1919, M-28 began in [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]] at a junction with then [[M-12 (Michigan highway)|M-12]] and ran roughly along the current alignment to end at [[M-15 (Michigan highway)|M-15]], {{convert|6.5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]].<ref name=\"MSHD19\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1919-07-01U |link= yes }}</ref> These two termini roughly correspond to the modern [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] and western [[U.S. Route 41 in Michigan|US&nbsp;41]] junctions respectively. M-28 was extended in 1927 along US&nbsp;41 into [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] and east over [[M-25 (Michigan highway)|M-25]] through [[Chatham, Michigan|Chatham]], [[Munising, Michigan|Munising]], and [[Newberry, Michigan|Newberry]], before ending in downtown [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]. At Negaunee, M-28 took the former routing of M-15 between [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]] and [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]] for {{convert|10|mi|km|0}} while US&nbsp;41 ran along a portion of [[M-35 (Michigan highway)|M-35]].<ref name=\"MSHD27\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1927-12-01 }}</ref> This southern loop routing of M-28 lasted until approximately 1936, when M-28 was moved to US&nbsp;41,<ref name=\"MSHD36-06\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1936-06-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> and the former route became [[County Road 492 (Marquette County, Michigan)|CR&nbsp;492]].<ref name=\"googleN\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Negaunee,+MI&ie=UTF8&z=12 |title=Negaunee, Michigan |access-date= July 1, 2008 }}</ref> A new routing of M-28 in the Newberry area opened later that year,<ref name=\"MSHD36-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1936-12-15 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> and a new M-28A (later [[M-28 Business (Newberry, Michigan)|Bus. M-28]]) existed until 1953.<ref name=\"MSHD53\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1953-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref> Another realignment in 1937 marked the transfer of M-28 out of downtown [[Ishpeming, Michigan|Ishpeming]] and Negaunee. This former routing later became [[M-28 Business (Ishpeming-Negaunee, Michigan)|Bus. M-28]].<ref name=\"MSHD37-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1937-12-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|M-178}}{{infobox road small\n|state=MI\n|type=M 1926\n|route=178\n|location=[[Wetmore, Michigan|Wetmore]]\u2013[[Munising, Michigan|Munising]]\n|length_mi=1.036\n|length_ref=<ref name=PRFA/>\n|formed={{circa|1936}}<ref name=MSHD36-06/>\n|deleted=1941<ref name=MSHD41-03/><ref name=MSHD41-12/>\n}}\nIn the late 1930s, a highway numbered '''M-178''' was designated between M-28 south of Munising to M-94 in town.<ref name=MSHD36-06/> In 1941, the routings of M-28 and [[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] were reversed between [[Harvey, Michigan|Harvey]] and Munising, and M-28 supplanted the M-178 designation completely.<ref name=\"MSHD41-03\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1941-03-21 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD41-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1941-12-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> Since then, M-28 has run along the lakeshore through [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]]. M-28 was extended along US&nbsp;2 to the state line at [[Ironwood, Michigan|Ironwood]], and the eastern end of M-28 through [[Brimley, Michigan|Brimley]] was moved to a new alignment ending at US&nbsp;2, in [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]] in 1942.<ref name=\"MSHD42-06\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1942-06-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> The eastern end was moved along US&nbsp;2 back to Sault Ste. Marie in 1948,<ref name=\"MSHD48-07\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1948-07-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> though the terminus was returned to Dafter in 1950.<ref name=\"MSHD50-04\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1950-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n[[File:M-28 & M-178.jpg |thumb|left|Junction between M-28 and M-178 just south of Munising before 1941]]\nFrom 1952 to 1962, M-28 crossed US&nbsp;2 at Wakefield going south and stopped at the [[Wisconsin]] border, connecting with a county road.<ref name=\"MSHD52-04\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1952-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref> This segment of the highway (now Gogebic CR&nbsp;519)<ref name=\"googleW\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Wakefield,+MI&ie=UTF8&z=13&iwloc=addr |title=Wakefield, Michigan |access-date= March 16, 2008 }}</ref> was transferred back to the county in 1962.<ref name=\"MSHD62\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1962 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> M-94 previously looped along Munising-Van Meer-Shingleton Road (now [[H-58 (Michigan county highway)|H-58]] and [[H-15 (Michigan county highway)|H-15]]) north of M-28 between Munising and Shingleton. This routing was abandoned on November 7, 1963 in favor of the current [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]].<ref name=\"ROWAC\">{{cite map |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |map-url = http://mdotwas1.mdot.state.mi.us/public/ROWFiles/files/Alger/Sheet056.pdf |map = Alger County |title = Right-of-Way File Application |date =  |sheet = 56 |scale = Scale not given |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |access-date = May 8, 2008 |map-format = PDF |oclc = 23853690 }}</ref> The last significant change to the M-28 routing occurred on March 3, 1989, when the eastern terminus was moved east to [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]].<ref name=\"ROWCC\">{{cite map |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |mapurl = http://mdotwas1.mdot.state.mi.us/public/ROWFiles/files/Titlesheets/Chippewa.pdf |map = Chippewa County |title = Right-of-Way File Application |at = Title sheet |access-date = May 8, 2008 |date = August 7, 1991 |map-format = PDF |scale = Scale not given |oclc = 12843824 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:US 41 M-28 Marquette roundabout.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the roundabout in Marquette as proposed]]\nMDOT unveiled plans on March 31, 2009, to rebuild the intersection between Front Street and the eastern end of the Marquette Bypass during 2010.<ref name=diem-2009-03-27>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/524905.html?nav=5006 |title = City Set to Upgrade Confusing Intersection |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |access-date = April 2, 2009 |date = March 27, 2009 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDsgMpd8?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/524905.html?nav=5006 |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> The previous intersection configuration dated back to the 1960s and had been labeled as \"dangerous and [causing] significant traffic delays\" by the designers of the replacement.<ref name=diem-2009-04-02>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |url = http://www.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/525269.html?nav=5006 |title = Residents Get Look at Plan for Roundabout |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = The Mining Journal |access-date = April 2, 2009 |date = April 1, 2009 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> A traffic study concluded in 2007 that the intersection would need either the roundabout or a traffic signal with several turning lanes to accommodate the traffic needs in the area. MDOT decided in favor of a two-lane, {{convert|150|ft|m|adj=on}} roundabout retaining the right-turn lanes from the previous intersection layout. These lanes will be used by right-turning traffic to bypass the circle at the center of the intersection.<ref name=diem-2009-04-02/>\n\nConstruction started on the project in May.<ref name=diem-2010-06-21>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Roundabout Work Progresses |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = June 21, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/545490.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDt6QdUL?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/545490.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> A section of the intersection was opened in July to traffic from the south that turns west.<ref name=diem-2010-07-17>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Routes Through Town Reopen |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = July 17, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/546414.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtG6MSF?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/546414.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> The lanes northbound into downtown were opened in the beginning of August,<ref name=diem-2010-08-06>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Open for Business: Motorists Take Measure of New Intersection |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = August 6, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547215.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtKFT6l?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547215.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> and the city held a ribbon cutting ceremony on August 19, 2010. The remaining lanes were opened the next day.<ref name=diem-2010-08-19>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = New Roundabout Celebrated with Ceremony |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = August 19, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547668.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtOKia0?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547668.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref>\n\n=== Historic bridges ===\nMDOT has highlighted five [[National Register of Historic Places|historic]] bridges along the route of M-28 on the MDOT website. In [[Interior Township, Michigan|Interior Township]], [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]], the highway crosses the [[Ontonagon River]] over a bridge built in 1929.  Designed by the State Highway Department and built by the firm of Meads and Anderson, the Ontonagon River Bridge is one of only three [[Arch bridges|steel arch]] bridges in Michigan. The main span arch is  {{convert|150|ft|m|0}} long.<ref name=\"mb1\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013Ontonagon River Bridge |date = April 19, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-29212--,00.html |access-date = January 28, 2008 }}</ref> A former routing of M-28 in [[Covington Township, Michigan|Covington Township]] crosses the Rock River. Although this section was bypassed by a new alignment of the trunkline in 1924, the bridge remains complete \"with corbeled bulkheads and six panels recessed in the concrete spandrel walls.\"<ref name=\"mb2\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = Old M-28\u2013Rock River Bridge |date = April 9, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-25653--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> The [[corbel]]s and [[spandrel]]s are decorative features found in the concrete sides of the bridge.\n\n[[Image:US 41 Peshekee Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Abandoned Peshekee River Bridge in [[Michigamme Township, Michigan|Michigamme Township]]|alt=A river flowing between two banks covered in vegetation and trees. The river flows under a concrete bridge resting on four support piers into a lake in the background.]]\n\nToday, drivers cannot use the [[Trunk Line Bridge No. 1|Peshekee River Bridge]] south of US&nbsp;41/M-28 in western [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]]'s [[Michigamme Township, Michigan|Michigamme Township]]. The bridge was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1999 as \"Trunk Line Bridge No. 1\" for its engineering and architectural significance.<ref name=\"NHS1\">{{cite web |author = National Park Service |title = National Register of Historic Places\u2014Michigan (MI), Marquette County |year = 1999 |work = [[National Register of Historic Places]] |url = http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/MI/Marquette/state.html |access-date = February 12, 2008 |author-link = National Park Service }}</ref> MDOT has listed it as \"one of Michigan's most important vehicular bridges.\"<ref name=\"mb3\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = US&nbsp;41\u2013Peshekee River Bridge |date = April 23, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-30382--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> It was the first bridge designed by the Michigan State Highway Department, the forerunner to MDOT, in 1914. It was bypassed by a newer bridge built over the Peshekee River on US&nbsp;41/M-28 subsequently abandoned as a roadway. The replacement bridge was bypassed and demolished in 1995.<ref name=\"AL&S\">{{cite web |author = A. Lindberg & Sons, Inc. |title = Projects |publisher = A. Lindberg & Sons, Inc |url = http://www.lindberginc.com/projects.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060619055255/http://lindberginc.com/projects.htm |archivedate = June 19, 2006 |access-date = February 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe next historic bridge listed by MDOT along M-28 is [[M-28\u2013Sand River Bridge|over the Sand River]] in [[Onota Township, Michigan|Onota Township]] in [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]]. While not visible to motorists, the bridge, constructed in 1939, is the longest rural rigid-frame span in Michigan.<ref name=\"mb4\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013Sand River Bridge |date = April 9, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-25541--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> Most bridges of this type were built in urban locations, and soil conditions in the state limit locations for this style of bridge. The [[M-28\u2013Tahquamenon River Bridge|bridge]] over the East Branch of the [[Tahquamenon River]] in [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] was built in 1926 as a \"formative exercise in what would evolve into a state standard design.\"<ref name=\"mb5\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013E. Br. Tahquamenon River Bridge |date = April 15, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-26681--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> The {{convert|55|ft|m|0|adj=on}} bridge was built with nine lines of [[I-beam]]s encased in concrete. Only one other bridge in Michigan was built with such concrete encasement.<ref name=\"mb5\"/>\n\n== Future ==\n[[File:Michigan 480 Marquette County.svg|thumb|left|80px|CR&nbsp;480 in Marquette County|alt=County Road 480 marker]]\nIn the August 24, 2005 edition, the [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]] ''Mining Journal''  reported that the [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] Board and the County Road Commission were negotiating with MDOT to transfer the jurisdiction of Marquette County Road&nbsp;480 to the state. Several routing options have been discussed, though all would make CR&nbsp;480 a part of M-28.<ref name=\"mj\">{{cite news |first = Pete |last = Mackin |title = CR&nbsp;480 Plan Taking Shape |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = The Mining Journal |date = August 24, 2005 |pages = A1+ |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> Cost was the primary reason given behind rerouting M-28 along CR&nbsp;480. \"The road commission receives about $50,000{{#tag:ref|Equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US-GDP|50000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}.{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}|group=lower-alpha}} a year in state gas tax money but spends about $100,000{{#tag:ref|Equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US-GDP|100000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}.{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}|group=lower-alpha}} to maintain CR&nbsp;480 because of the type and volume of traffic it receives.\"<ref name=\"mj\"/> Handing CR&nbsp;480 over to the state would shift the maintenance costs to the state, as well.<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\nMDOT has indicated that it has not requested jurisdiction, but rather if it assumed control of the route, the community would need to support a through-route. Several proposals have arisen, including creating a \"spur\" from US&nbsp;41/M-28 through the east end of Ishpeming to meet CR&nbsp;480 west of Negaunee. This spur would pass through recently reopened former mining \"caving grounds\", and to the south of the Mather A & B Mine complex.<ref name=\"mj\"/> According to Gerry Corkin, Marquette County Board Chairman, \"the land that was purchased by Ishpeming and Negaunee, the mining company land, this has the potential to help in the development of that if this is compatible. I think both cities will be interested in taking a look at what the land uses are and where this [spur] would push through.\"<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\nThe spur proposal would open land to development between the downtown areas of the two cities. If jurisdiction is transferred, and M-28 is routed over CR&nbsp;480 as proposed, M-28 would leave the concurrency with US&nbsp;41 near [[Teal Lake (Michigan)|Teal Lake]] in Negaunee, and cross the caving grounds west of downtown to connect to Rail Street. Rail Street would serve as the connector to CR&nbsp;480, which ends at the intersection of Rail and Ann streets and Healey Avenue. Proposals indicate two routing options for the east end of CR&nbsp;480. One would route M-28 back along US&nbsp;41 from Beaver Grove north of the CR&nbsp;480 eastern terminus to the existing M-28 in Harvey. A second would route it along CR&nbsp;551/Cherry Creek Road from CR&nbsp;480 to M-28 in Harvey.<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\n== Business loops ==\n{{Main article|U.S. Route 41 Business (Marquette, Michigan)| M-28 Business (Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee, Michigan)| M-28 Business (Newberry, Michigan) |l1=Business US&nbsp;41 in Marquette|l2=Business M-28 in Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|l3=Business M-28 in Newberry}}\nThere have been three [[business loop]]s for M-28: Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee, Marquette and Newberry. Only the business loop serving Ishpeming and Negaunee is still a state-maintained trunkline. US&nbsp;41/M-28 was relocated to bypass the two cities' downtowns in 1937.<ref name=\"MSHD37-12\"/><ref name=\"MSHD37-05\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1937-05-15 |section= B5}}</ref> The highway through downtown Ishpeming and Negaunee later carried the ALT&nbsp;US&nbsp;41/ALT&nbsp;M-28 designation before being designated Bus. M-28 in 1958.<ref name=\"MDOT51\">{{cite map |author = Michigan State Highway Department |location = Lansing |publisher = Michigan State Highway Department |title = City of Ishpeming Act 51 Map |year = 1951 |scale = Scale not given }}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD58\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1958 |section=C5}}</ref> The western end of the business loop was transferred to local government control when Bus. M-28 was moved along Lakeshore Drive in 1999.<ref name=\"MSABR\">{{cite web |author = State Administrative Board |date = n.d. |title = State Administrative Board Resolutions, 1940\u2013Present |location = Lansing |publisher = State of Michigan |url = http://www.michigan.gov/documents/resolution_list_155716_7.pdf |access-date = February 13, 2008 |author-link = Michigan State Administrative Board }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marquette, Michigan - Buildings.jpg|thumb|right|The former Bus. US&nbsp;41 along Washington Street in downtown Marquette|alt=A city street with parked vehicles on either side in front of a series of stone buildings]]\nBus. US&nbsp;41 in Marquette was first shown on a map in 1964 after the construction of the Marquette Bypass.<ref name=\"MSHD63\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1963 |section=B6}}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD64\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1964 |section=B6}}</ref> It was later designated Bus. US&nbsp;41/Bus. M-28 on a map in 1975;<ref name=\"MDOT75\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1975 |inset= Marquette}}</ref> this second designation was removed from maps by 1982.<ref name=\"MDOT82M\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1982 |inset= Marquette}}</ref> The entire business loop was turned back to local control in a \"route swap\" between the City of Marquette and MDOT announced in early 2005. The proposal transferred jurisdiction on the unsigned [[M-554 (Michigan highway)|M-554]] and the business route from the state to the city. The state would take jurisdiction over a segment of McClellan Avenue to be used to extend [[M-553 (Michigan highway)|M-553]] to US&nbsp;41/M-28. In addition, MDOT would pay $2.5&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|2500000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}) for reconstruction work planned for 2007.<ref name=\"swanson\">{{cite news |last = Swanson |first = Scott |title = City to Get $2.5&nbsp;Million |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = April 26, 2005 |page = A1 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> The transfer would increase Marquette's operational and maintenance liability expenses by $26,000 (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US-GDP|26000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}) and place the financial burden of the future replacement of a stop light on the city.<ref name=\"swanson\"/> On October 10, 2005, MDOT and Marquette transferred jurisdiction over the three roadways. As a result, Bus. US&nbsp;41 was decommissioned when the local government took control over Washington and Front streets.<ref name=\"jtpr\">{{cite press release |last = Garner |first = Dawn |title = MDOT and City of Marquette Complete Jurisdictional Transfer |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |date = November 9, 2005 |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-129975--,00.html |access-date = July 31, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070314203544/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0%2C1607%2C7-151-9620_11057-129975--%2C00.html |archivedate = March 14, 2007 |df = }}</ref> As a result of the decommissioning, the 2006 maps did not show the now former business loop.<ref name=\"MDOT06\">{{cite MDOT map |year=2006 |section=B4}}</ref>\n\nThe Newberry Bus. M-28 was designated from 1936 until 1952 as M-28A.<ref name=\"MSHD36-12\"/> The MSHD maps of the time showed it signed as Bus. M-28 in 1952 before it was turned back to local control in 1953.<ref name=\"MSHD53\"/><ref name=\"MSHD52-10\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1952-10-01 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n== Major intersections ==\n{{MIinttop|ref=<ref name=\"PRFA\">{{cite MDOT PRFA |link= yes |access-date= April 13, 2010}}</ref>}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Gogebic\n|location=Wakefield\n|type=concur\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|2|Tour|LSCT|dir2=west|name2=Putnam Street|city1=Ironwood|city2=Iron River}}<br/>{{jct|state=MI|CR|519|county1=Gogebic|dir1=south|name1=Sunday Lake Street|nolink1=y}}\n|notes=Western end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Ontonagon\n|cspan=3\n|location=Merriweather\n|mile=16.281\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|64|dir1=south|city1=Marenisco}}\n|notes=Western end of M-64 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bergland\n|mile=20.422\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|64|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=White Pine|city2=Ontonagon|name2=Ash Street}}\n|notes=Eastern end of M-64 and LSCT concurrencies }}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bruce Crossing\n|mile=39.990\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|45|city1=Ontonagon|city2=Watersmeet}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Houghton\n|location=Kenton\n|type=concur\n|mile=56.394\n|mile2=56.596\n|road={{jct|state=MI|FFH|16}}\n|notes=Marked as H-16 on MDOT maps; short concurrency through Kenton}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Baraga\n|cspan=2\n|location=Covington\n|lspan=2\n|mile=74.330\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|141|dir1=south|city1=Crystal Falls|city2=Iron Mountain}}\n|notes=Western end of US&nbsp;141 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=78.484\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|41|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Baraga|city2=Houghton}}<br/>{{jct|state=MI|US|141|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US&nbsp;141; western end of US&nbsp;41 and LSCT concurrencies}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Marquette\n|cspan=10\n|location=Humboldt Township\n|mile=106.927\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|95|dir1=south|city1=Republic|city2=Iron Mountain}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-95}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Ishpeming\n|mile=118.614\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M-Bus|28|dab1=Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|name1=Lakeshore Drive|city1=Ishpeming}}\n|notes=Western terminus of Bus. M-28}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Negaunee\n|lspan=2\n|mile=122.215\n|road={{jct|state=MI|MI-Bus|28|dab1=Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|name1=Teal Lake Avenue|city1=Negaunee}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Bus. M-28}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=122.957\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CR|492|county1=Marquette|dir1=east|name1=Maas Street|city1=Marquette}}\n|notes=Former routing along Marquette\u2013Negaunee Road}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Negaunee Township\n|mile=125.840\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|35|dir1=south|city1=Palmer|city2=Gwinn}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-35}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Marquette Township\n|ctdab=Marquette\n|mile=130.486\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CR|492|county1=Marquette|city1=Negaunee}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Marquette\n|lspan=3\n|mile=131.930\n|road=Washington Street\n|notes=Western terminus of former [[U.S. Route 41 Business (Marquette, Michigan)|Bus. US&nbsp;41]]}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=132.312\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|553|dir1=south|city1=KI Saywer|city2=Gwinn|name1=McClellan Avenue}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-553}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=133.674\n|road=Front Street\n|notes=Eastern terminus of former Bus. US&nbsp;41}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Harvey\n|mile=137.925\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|41|dir1=south|city1=Escanaba}}\n|notes=Eastern end of US&nbsp;41 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Alger\n|cspan=6\n|location=Onota Township\n|mile=159.637\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-01|dir1=south|city1=Chatham|name1=Rock River Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of H-01}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Au Train\n|mile=164.541\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-03|dir1=south|city1=Au Train|county1=Alger|name1=Au Train Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of H-03}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Munising\n|mile=175.903\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-58|county1=Alger|dir1=east|city1=Grand Marais|name1=Munising Road}}\n|notes=Western terminus of H-58<br />Provides access to [[Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Munising Township\n|mile=176.939\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|94|dir1=west|city1=Chatham}}\n|notes=Western end of M-94 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Wetmore\n|mile=178.849\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-13|FFH|13|county1=Alger|city1=Nahma|name2=Connors Road}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Shingleton\n|mile=186.409\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|94|CDH|H-15|county2=Alger|dir1=south|dir2=north|city1=Manistique|city2=Van Meer|name2=Van Meer Road}}\n|notes=Eastern end of M-94 concurrency<br />Western end of the Seney Stretch}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Schoolcraft\n|cspan=3\n|location=Hiawatha Township\n|mile=195.595\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-52|county1=Schoolcraft|dir1=north}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Seney\n|lspan=2\n|mile=210.984\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|77|dir1=south|city1=Blaney Park}}\n|notes=Eastern end of the Seney Stretch<br />Eastern end of a {{convert|0.36|mi|adj=on}} concurrency to cross Fox River}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=211.344\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|77|Tour|LSCT-Spur|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Grand Marais}}\n|notes=Western end of M-77 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Luce\n|cspan=3\n|location=Lakefield Township\n|ctdab=Luce\n|mile=226.619\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-33|county1=Luce|dir1=south|city1=Germfask|name1=CR&nbsp;135 / Manistique Lakes Road}}\n|notes=Former terminus of [[M-135 (Michigan highway)|M-135]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Pentland Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=230.927\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|117|dir1=south|city1=Engadine}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-117}}\n{{MIint\n|type=concur\n|mile=233.916\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|123|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Newberry|name2=Newberry Avenue}}\n|notes=Western junction with M-123; eastern end of LSCT concurrency; provides access to [[Tahquamenon Falls State Park]]}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Chippewa\n|cspan=5\n|location=Chippewa Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|type=concur\n|mile=257.648\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|123|Tour|LSCT|dir2=north|city1=Paradise|city2=Trout Lake}}\n|notes=Eastern junction with M-123; western end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Superior Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|mile=279.943\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|221|dir1=north|city1=Brimley}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of M-221}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Dafter Township\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=287.484\n|road={{jct|state=MI|I|75|Tour|LSCT|dir2=north|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace}}\n|notes=Exit 386 on I-75; eastern end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=287.873\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-63|county1=Chippewa|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace|name1=[[Mackinac Trail]]}}\n|notes=Former [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bruce Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|mile=290.373\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|129|Tour|LHCT|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace|name1=McKnight Road}}\n|notes=}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Michigan Highways}}\n*[[List of longest state highways in the United States]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|M-28 (Michigan highway)|M-28}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title, inline}}\n*{{Osmrelation-inline|226345|M-28}}\n* [http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-028.html M-28] at Michigan Highways\n* [http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-178.html Former M-178] at Michigan Highways\n<!--* [http://www.state-ends.com/michigan/m/28/ M-28] at Michigan Highway Ends-->\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M028}}\n[[Category:M-28 (Michigan highway)|*]]\n[[Category:State highways in Michigan|028]]\n[[Category:Lake Superior Circle Tour]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Gogebic County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Ontonagon County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Houghton County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Baraga County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Marquette County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Alger County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Schoolcraft County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Luce County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Chippewa County, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Highway in Michigan, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MI\n|type=M\n|route=28\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=240|frame-lat=46.455|frame-long=-87.144|zoom=6|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/M-28 (Michigan highway)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=M-28 highlighted in red\n|map_alt=A map of the Upper Peninsula of Michigan showing M-28 in red crossing east\u2013west, intersecting an Interstate on the east end\n|length_mi=290.373\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"PRFA\"/>\n|established={{circa|July 1, 1919}}<ref name=\"MSHD19\"/>\n|tourist=[[File:Lake Superior Circle Tour.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] [[Lake Superior Circle Tour]]\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MI|US|2}} at [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|45}} at [[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|141}} near [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|41}} in [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]] \n*{{jct|state=MI|M|35}} near [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|41}} in [[Harvey, Michigan|Harvey]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|75}} near [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]]\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MI|M|129}} near [[Sault Ste Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]\n|counties=[[Gogebic County, Michigan|Gogebic]], [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon]], [[Houghton County, Michigan|Houghton]], [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga]], [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette]], [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger]], [[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft]], [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce]], [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa]]\n|previous_type=M\n|previous_route=27\n|next_type=M\n|next_route=29\n|browse={{mi browse|previous_type=M 1926|previous_route=177|route={{nowrap|M-178}}|next_type=M|next_route=179}}\n\n}}\n\n'''M-28''' is an east\u2013west [[Michigan Highway System|state trunkline highway]] that traverses nearly all of the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper Peninsula]] of the U.S. state of [[Michigan]], from [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]] to near [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]] in [[Bruce Township, Chippewa County, Michigan|Bruce Township]]. Along with [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US Highway 2]] (US&nbsp;2), M-28 forms a pair of primary highways linking the Upper Peninsula from end to end, providing a major access route for traffic from Michigan and Canada along the southern shore of [[Lake Superior]]. M-28 is the longest state trunkline in Michigan numbered with the \"M-\" prefix at {{convert|290.373|mi|km|3}}. The entire highway is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], while three sections of M-28 are part of the [[Lake Superior Circle Tour]]. M-28 also carries two memorial highway designations along its route.\n\nThroughout its course across the Upper Peninsula, M-28 passes through forested woodlands, bog swamps, urbanized areas, and along the Lake Superior shoreline. Sections of roadway cross the [[Ottawa National Forest]] and both units of the [[Hiawatha National Forest]]. Some of the other landmarks accessible from M-28 include the Seney Stretch, [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]] and several historic bridges.\n\nM-28 is an original trunkline designation, dating to the 1919 formation of the state's trunkline system. The original highway was much shorter than the current version. M-28 was expanded eastward to the Sault Ste. Marie area in the late 1920s. The western end has been expanded twice to different locations on the [[Wisconsin]] state line. Other changes along the routing have led to the creation of three different [[business loop]]s at various times, with one still extant. Future changes, proposed by Marquette County but not accepted by the [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT), could see M-28 rerouted over County Road&nbsp;480 (CR&nbsp;480).\n\n== Route description ==\n[[File:M-28 Trout Creek.jpg|thumb|left|Clouds brewing over M-28 in western Ontonagon County|alt=a highway curving over the crest of a hill flanked by telephone poles on either side. There is a white road sign on the right side of the road and storm clouds in the sky.]]\nM-28 is a major highway for Michigan and Canadian traffic along the south shore of Lake Superior. It forms the northern half of a pair of primary trunklines linking the Upper Peninsula from end to end; [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] is the southern partner.<ref name=\"MDOT2\"/> The {{convert| 290.373|mi|km|adj=on}} highway comprises mostly two lanes, undivided except for sections that are [[Concurrency (road)|concurrent]] with [[U.S. Route 41 in Michigan|US&nbsp;41]] near [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]]. The \"Marquette Bypass\" portion of US&nbsp;41/M-28 is a four-lane [[Limited-access road|expressway]], and segments of the highway in [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] have four lanes.<ref name=\"MDOT14\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 2014 |sections= C1\u2013C11 }}</ref> The entire route is part of the National Highway System,<ref name=\"NHS\">{{cite map |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = National Highway System, Michigan |date = April 23, 2006 |location = Lansing |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |format = PDF |scale = Scale not given |access-date = February 4, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/6AqxSurw0?url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |archivedate = September 21, 2012 |df = }}</ref> and three sections of the trunkline are part of the Lake Superior Circle Tour.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n=== Western terminus to Shingleton ===\nIn the west, M-28 begins at a signalized intersection with US&nbsp;2 in Wakefield. Heading north, the highway passes Sunday Lake heading out of town. After crossing into southwestern [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]] and the [[Eastern Time Zone]], the trunkline highway skirts the northern shore of [[Lake Gogebic]], running concurrently with [[M-64 (Michigan highway)|M-64]]. The first section of M-28 designated as a part of the Lake Superior Circle Tour is from the western terminus to the eastern junction with M-64 in [[Bergland, Michigan|Bergland]], where the Circle Tour turns north along M-64, leaving M-28. Here, M-28 has its lowest traffic counts; within the 2013 MDOT survey, the road is listed with only an [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT) of 1,425 vehicles on a section of highway between Bergland and the [[U.S. Route 45 in Michigan|US&nbsp;45]] intersection in [[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]].<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author = Bureau of Transportation Planning |url = http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title = Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |year = 2008 |access-date = December 19, 2014 }}</ref> The trunkline runs through heavily forested areas of southern [[Houghton County, Michigan|Houghton]] and [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga counties]]. At the eastern junction with US&nbsp;41 near Covington, M-28 receives the Circle Tour designation again<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/> and exits the [[Ottawa National Forest]].<ref name=\"RM13\">{{cite map |author = [[Rand McNally]] |title = The Road Atlas |map = Michigan |edition = 2013 Walmart |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally |year = 2013 |scale = 1:1,267,200 and 1:1900,800 |sections = C10\u2013C14, D1\u2013D9 |pages = 50\u201351 |isbn = 0-528-00626-6 |oclc = 773666955 }}</ref>\n\nIn Baraga and Marquette counties, US&nbsp;41/M-28 passes through hilly terrain before entering the urban areas of [[Ishpeming, Michigan|Ishpeming]], [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]] and Marquette.<ref name=\"MDOT2\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = Chapter One: Introduction |work = US&nbsp;41/M-28 Access Management Plan |date = April 28, 2004 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_US-41_M28_chapter1_108596_7.pdf |access-date = January 18, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071223031233/http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_US-41_M28_chapter1_108596_7.pdf |archivedate = December 23, 2007 }}</ref> Approximately 13,000\u201317,000&nbsp;vehicles use this section from Ishpeming eastward through Negaunee. West of the city of Marquette, US&nbsp;41/M-28 had a peak 2013 AADT of 32,805&nbsp;vehicles in [[Marquette Township, Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette Township]] along a retail and business corridor. This peak level is sustained until the start of the Marquette Bypass, where the traffic returns to the 16,500-vehicle and higher levels seen in Ishpeming and Negaunee. South of the city of Marquette, traffic counts once again climb to 19,620&nbsp;vehicles. In [[Chocolay Township, Michigan|Chocolay Township]] the AADT drops to 8,840&nbsp;vehicles before tapering off to 3,065&nbsp;vehicles by the county line.<ref name=\"TMIS\"/>\n\nAt the Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee city line, M-28 changes memorial highway designations. From the western terminus to this point, M-28 is called the \"Veterans Memorial Highway\", but it becomes the \"D. J. Jacobetti Memorial Highway\" to honor the longest-serving member of the [[Michigan Legislature]], [[Dominic Jacobetti|Dominic J. Jacobetti]].<ref name=\"memorial\">{{cite book |last = Barnett |first = LeRoy |year = 2004 |title = A Drive Down Memory Lane: The Named State and Federal Highways of Michigan |location = Allegan Forest, Michigan |publisher = Priscilla Press |pages = 115\u201316, 226 |isbn = 1-886167-24-9 |oclc = 57425393 }}</ref><ref name=\"jacobetti\">{{cite news |last = Prusi |first = Renee |title = End of an Era: Jacobetti Dies This Morning |date = November 28, 1994 |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |location = Marquette, Michigan |pages = 1A, 5A |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> The Jacobetti Highway designation ends at the eastern M-123 junction in [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]].<ref name=\"PA142\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Legislature |title = Michigan Memorial Highway Act (PA 142 of 2001) |url = http://legislature.mi.gov/doc.aspx?mcl-Act-142-of-2001 |date = October 26, 2001 |access-date = June 6, 2008 |author-link = Michigan Legislature }}</ref>\n[[File:Hiawatha National Forest.jpg|right|thumb|[[Hiawatha National Forest]] road sign on M-28/[[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] in [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]] west of [[Shingleton, Michigan|Shingleton]]|alt=A brown and white wooden sign for the Hiawatha National Forest mounted on a stone base. The sign is installed on the right side of a highway between the road and the forest on the far right.]]\n\nBetween Marquette and [[Munising, Michigan|Munising]], M-28 closely parallels the Lake Superior shoreline, providing scenic views of the lake and its \"lonesome sandy beaches\".<ref name=\"huntsPR\">{{cite book |ref = harv |last1 = Hunt |first1 = Mary |last2 = Hunt |first2 = Don |year = 2007 |title = Hunts' Guide to Michigan's Upper Peninsula |publisher = Midwestern Guides |location = Albion, Michigan |chapter-url = http://hunts-upguide.com/munising_pictured_rocks_national_lakeshore.html |chapter = Munising\u2014Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore |url = http://hunts-upguide.com/ |access-date = July 22, 2008 |last-author-amp = y }}</ref><ref name=\"fowler\">{{cite news |last = Fowler |first = Brenda |title = Endless Trails To Open Water |url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05EEDD1F3EF93AA15755C0A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = June 29, 1997 |access-date = February 20, 2008 |issn = 0362-4331 |oclc = 1645522 }}</ref> The Lakenenland Sculpture Park is located in [[Chocolay Township, Michigan|Chocolay Township]] near Shot Point in eastern Marquette County. This roadside attraction is owned by Tom Lakenen and features fanciful works of art made of scrap iron.<ref name=\"huntsL\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/marquette_lakenenland.html \"Lakenenland\"].}}</ref> Near the community of [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]], M-28 crosses into the western unit of the [[Hiawatha National Forest]].<ref name=\"RM13\"/> West of Munising is a ferry dock offering transport to the [[Grand Island National Recreation Area]], and at Munising there is easy access to [[Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore]]. The roadway also features [[variable-message sign]]s to warn motorists of winter weather-related traffic closures along the lakeshore. Installed at the US&nbsp;41 and [[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] junctions, the signs advise motorists which sections of roadway are closed. Per MDOT policy, only [[Winter service vehicle|snowplows]] are allowed on these sections during a closure.<ref name=\"MDOT3\">{{cite press release |first = Dawn |last = Garner |title = MDOT and MSP Prepare for Bad Weather on M-28 |date = November 23, 2005 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-130826--,00.html |access-date = January 19, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224094924/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-130826--,00.html |archivedate = December 24, 2007 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The highway exits the Hiawatha National Forest at the [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]]\u2013[[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft County]] line along the Seney Stretch.<ref name=\"RM13\"/>\n\n=== Seney Stretch ===\n[[File:seney Stretch1.jpg|thumb|left|The Seney Stretch along M-28|alt=A straight roadway leading away to the horizon with trees on either side of the road]]\nThe portion of M-28 between [[Seney, Michigan|Seney]] and [[Shingleton, Michigan|Shingleton]], called the Seney Stretch, is {{convert|25|mi|km|0}}<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&hl=en&saddr=Shingleton,+mi&daddr=Seney,+mi&ie=UTF8&z=10&om=1 |title= Overview Map of the Seney Stretch |access-date= September 15, 2006 }}</ref> of \"straight-as-an-arrow highway\"<ref name=\"Dennis\">*{{cite book |last = Dennis |first = Jerry |title = The River Home: An Angler's Explorations |publisher = St Martin's Press |date = June 1998 |isbn = 0-312-18594-4 |oclc = 38438636 |edition = 1st |location = New York |at = n.p. }}</ref> across the [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge|Great Manistique Swamp]], \"though others claim it's {{convert|50|mi|km|disp=x| [|]}}, only because it seems longer.\"<ref name=\"Spalding\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Spalding |title= You Haven't Lived Here Until... You've Driven the Seney Stretch |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] |date=August 26, 2006 |page=4A |issn= 1055-2758 |id= {{oclc| 10345127| 137343179}} }}</ref> The Seney Stretch is the longest such section of highway in the state, and \"one of the longest stretches of curveless highway east of the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]].\"<ref name=\"Carter\">*{{cite book |title = A Historical Guide to the Seney Stretch |first = James L. |last = Carter |year = 2004 |publisher = Pilot Press |location = Marquette, Michigan |oclc = 57178325 |page = 1 }}</ref> The highway is often cited as the \"state's most boring route\" according to the Michigan Economic Development Corporation (MEDC) and ''Hunts' Guide''.<ref name=\"MEDC\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Economic Development Corporation |title = Michigan Fall Color Tours: Munising, Newberry, Grand Marais |year = 2006 |work = Pure Michigan Travel |publisher = Michigan Economic Development Corporation |url = http://www.michigan.org/travel/drivingtours/detail.asp?cid=07E9B11E-0EE0-4F08-B88D-7DA087A490D6&da=y&m=9;1 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061221021805/http://www.michigan.org/travel/drivingtours/detail.asp?cid=07E9B11E-0EE0-4F08-B88D-7DA087A490D6&da=y&m=9%3B1 |archivedate = December 21, 2006 |access-date = July 22, 2008 |url-status = dead |df =  |author-link = Michigan Economic Development Corporation }}</ref><ref name=\"huntsSS\"/> The straightness and flatness over a great distance are given as reasons for the reputation of this stretch as boring.<ref name=\"huntsSS\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/shingleton.html \"Shingleton\"].}}</ref>\n\nThe road across the swamp was constructed parallel to the line of the [[Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway]] (later the [[Soo Line Railroad]]). It was first numbered as a part of [[M-25 (Michigan highway)|M-25]] when that designation was used along today's M-28 east of US&nbsp;41. The most significant changes made to the stretch since its original construction were the addition of [[Passing lane|passing relief lanes]] and a full-scale, year-round [[rest area]] in 1999.<ref name=\"mdot\">{{cite press release |first = Bill |last = Shreck |title = New Seney Rest Area Brings Year 'Round Relief to M-28 in the Upper Peninsula |date = May 28, 1999 |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-95119--,00.html |access-date = September 15, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070315042130/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0%2C1607%2C7-151-9620_11057-95119--%2C00.html |archivedate = March 15, 2007 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref>\n\nPart of the Seney Stretch forms the northern border of the [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref name=\"SNWRV\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = Visitor Information |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/VisInfo.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080522073254/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/VisInfo.htm |archivedate = May 22, 2008 |date = August 15, 2007 |access-date = July 22, 2008 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |author-link = United States Fish and Wildlife Service }}</ref>  Established in 1935, this refuge is a managed [[wetland]] in [[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft County]].<ref name=\"Rosentreter\">{{cite journal |ref = Rosentreter |last = Rosentreter |first = Roger L. |title = Roosevelt's Tree Army: Michigan's Civilian Conservation Corps |date = May\u2013June 1986 |journal = [[Michigan History magazine|Michigan History]] |url = http://www.michigan.gov/hal/0,1607,7-160-17451_18670_18793-53515--,00.html |access-date = December 3, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071101015836/http://www.michigan.gov/hal/0%2C1607%2C7-160-17451_18670_18793-53515--%2C00.html |location = Lansing |publisher = [[Michigan Department of State]] |issn = 0026-2196 |oclc = 1757361 |archivedate = November 1, 2007 |url-status = dead |df = }}\n</ref> It has an area of {{convert|95212|acre|km2|0}},<ref name=\"SNWRFS\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = Fact Sheet |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/factsheet.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229130419/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/factsheet.htm |archivedate = February 29, 2008 |date = August 17, 2007 |access-date = March 18, 2008 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service }}</ref> and contains the Strangmoor Bog [[National Natural Landmark]] within its boundaries.<ref name=\"FWS\">{{cite web |author = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |title = About Us |date = February 3, 2011 |url = http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/about_us.html |access-date = February 23, 2011 |work = Seney National Wildlife Refuge |publisher = United States Fish and Wildlife Service |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110320093458/http://www.fws.gov/midwest/seney/about_us.html |archivedate = March 20, 2011 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Seney to eastern terminus ===\n[[File:M-28 McMillan.jpg|thumb|right|A passing lane on M-28 westbound near McMillan|alt=A roadway curving down a slight incline and around a bend. On the side of the road are a series of sign posts with the M-28 reassurance marker, a yellow diamond with arrows indicating the traffic directions and a yellow diamond with an arrow warning of the curve in the road.]]\nPast Seney, M-28 once again enters woodlands on the eastern end of the Upper Peninsula. In [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce County]], the roadway passes through the community of [[McMillan Township, Luce County, Michigan|McMillan]] en route to [[Newberry, Michigan|Newberry]]. The Circle Tour departs M-28 to follow [[M-123 (Michigan highway)|M-123]] at Newberry, looping north to the [[Tahquamenon Falls State Park]]. East of town, the road passes Luce County Airport off of Luce CR&nbsp;399. From there, M-28 crosses the east and west branches of the Sage River and passes south of [[McMillan Township, Luce County, Michigan|Soo Junction]], before the [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] border.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\nIn Chippewa County, M-28 begins bending slightly east-northeastward. Hulbert Lake is located south of [[Hulbert, Michigan|Hulbert]]; north of the lake, the highway enters the eastern unit of the Hiawatha National Forest.<ref name=\"RM13\"/> At the eastern junction of M-28 and M-123 near [[Eckerman, Michigan|Eckerman]] and [[Strongs, Michigan|Strongs]], the Circle Tour returns to M-28 and the D.J. Jacobetti Memorial Highway designation ends. The highway leaves the eastern unit of the Hiawatha National Forest between the communities of [[Raco, Michigan|Raco]] and [[Brimley, Michigan|Brimley]].<ref name=\"RM13\"/> [[M-221 (Michigan highway)|M-221]] leads north from the main highway on an old routing of M-28 to connect to the community of Brimley and the [[Bay Mills Indian Community]]. [[Brimley State Park]] is just east of Brimley on the old 6&nbsp;Mile&nbsp;Road alignment of M-28.<ref name=\"BSP\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Natural Resources |title = Brimley State Park Detail |url = http://www.michigandnr.com/parksandtrails/details.aspx?id=414&type=SPRK |publisher = Michigan Department of Natural Resources |access-date = March 18, 2008 }}</ref> The highway meets [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|Interstate&nbsp;75]] (I-75) at exit 386, and the Lake Superior Circle Tour departs M-28 to follow I-75. This interchange is just west of [[H-63 (Michigan county highway)|H-63]]/[[Mackinac Trail]], a former segment of US&nbsp;2. M-28 continues {{convert|3|mi|km|spell=in}} farther to its eastern terminus with [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]].<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n=== Services ===\n[[File:Scott Falls.jpg|thumb|left|Scott Falls next to a roadside park near [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]]|alt=A rock outcropping overhanging a small pool of water with a waterfall cascading into the pool]]\nAlong the routing of M-28, MDOT has established several roadside parks and rest areas. Two of these are in Ontonagon County near [[Ewen, Michigan|Ewen]] and [[Trout Creek, Michigan|Trout Creek]].<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/> A park with a picnic area and a footbridge lies near Tioga Creek in [[Baraga County, Michigan|Baraga County]] east of the US&nbsp;41 junction.<ref name=\"huntsTC\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/michigamme_tioga_river_roadside_park_and_waterfall.html \"Tioga River Roadside Park and Waterfall\"].}}</ref> In [[Michigamme, Michigan|Michigamme]] a scenic turnout and a roadside park overlook [[Lake Michigamme]], and along Lake Superior south of Marquette is a tourist information center built as a log cabin. East of the [[H-01 (Michigan county highway)|H-01]] junction in [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]] is a roadside park that includes [[Scott Falls]].<ref name=\"huntsSF\">{{harvp|Hunt|Hunt|2007|loc=[http://hunts-upguide.com/au_train_scott_falls__the_face_in_the_rock_m_dot_harold_rathfoot_roadside_park.html \"Au Train\u2014Scott Falls, The Face in the Rock, MDOT Harold Rathfoot Roadside Park\"].}}</ref> Further east, a year-round rest area is located on the western end of the Seney Stretch. Three other roadside parks lie east of Harvey in [[Shelter Bay, Michigan|Shelter Bay]], on the shores of Deer Lake and west of Newberry.<ref name=\"MDOT14\"/>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Mainline history ===\nFormed by July 1, 1919, M-28 began in [[Wakefield, Michigan|Wakefield]] at a junction with then [[M-12 (Michigan highway)|M-12]] and ran roughly along the current alignment to end at [[M-15 (Michigan highway)|M-15]], {{convert|6.5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Covington, Michigan|Covington]].<ref name=\"MSHD19\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1919-07-01U |link= yes }}</ref> These two termini roughly correspond to the modern [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] and western [[U.S. Route 41 in Michigan|US&nbsp;41]] junctions respectively. M-28 was extended in 1927 along US&nbsp;41 into [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] and east over [[M-25 (Michigan highway)|M-25]] through [[Chatham, Michigan|Chatham]], [[Munising, Michigan|Munising]], and [[Newberry, Michigan|Newberry]], before ending in downtown [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]. At Negaunee, M-28 took the former routing of M-15 between [[Negaunee, Michigan|Negaunee]] and [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]] for {{convert|10|mi|km|0}} while US&nbsp;41 ran along a portion of [[M-35 (Michigan highway)|M-35]].<ref name=\"MSHD27\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1927-12-01 }}</ref> This southern loop routing of M-28 lasted until approximately 1936, when M-28 was moved to US&nbsp;41,<ref name=\"MSHD36-06\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1936-06-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> and the former route became [[County Road 492 (Marquette County, Michigan)|CR&nbsp;492]].<ref name=\"googleN\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Negaunee,+MI&ie=UTF8&z=12 |title=Negaunee, Michigan |access-date= July 1, 2008 }}</ref> A new routing of M-28 in the Newberry area opened later that year,<ref name=\"MSHD36-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1936-12-15 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> and a new M-28A (later [[M-28 Business (Newberry, Michigan)|Bus. M-28]]) existed until 1953.<ref name=\"MSHD53\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1953-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref> Another realignment in 1937 marked the transfer of M-28 out of downtown [[Ishpeming, Michigan|Ishpeming]] and Negaunee. This former routing later became [[M-28 Business (Ishpeming-Negaunee, Michigan)|Bus. M-28]].<ref name=\"MSHD37-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1937-12-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|M-178}}{{infobox road small\n|state=MI\n|type=M 1926\n|route=178\n|location=[[Wetmore, Michigan|Wetmore]]\u2013[[Munising, Michigan|Munising]]\n|length_mi=1.036\n|length_ref=<ref name=PRFA/>\n|formed={{circa|1936}}<ref name=MSHD36-06/>\n|deleted=1941<ref name=MSHD41-03/><ref name=MSHD41-12/>\n}}\nIn the late 1930s, a highway numbered '''M-178''' was designated between M-28 south of Munising to M-94 in town.<ref name=MSHD36-06/> In 1941, the routings of M-28 and [[M-94 (Michigan highway)|M-94]] were reversed between [[Harvey, Michigan|Harvey]] and Munising, and M-28 supplanted the M-178 designation completely.<ref name=\"MSHD41-03\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1941-03-21 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD41-12\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1941-12-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> Since then, M-28 has run along the lakeshore through [[Au Train, Michigan|Au Train]]. M-28 was extended along US&nbsp;2 to the state line at [[Ironwood, Michigan|Ironwood]], and the eastern end of M-28 through [[Brimley, Michigan|Brimley]] was moved to a new alignment ending at US&nbsp;2, in [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]] in 1942.<ref name=\"MSHD42-06\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1942-06-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> The eastern end was moved along US&nbsp;2 back to Sault Ste. Marie in 1948,<ref name=\"MSHD48-07\">{{cite MDOT map |date=1948-07-01 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> though the terminus was returned to Dafter in 1950.<ref name=\"MSHD50-04\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1950-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n[[File:M-28 & M-178.jpg |thumb|left|Junction between M-28 and M-178 just south of Munising before 1941]]\nFrom 1952 to 1962, M-28 crossed US&nbsp;2 at Wakefield going south and stopped at the [[Wisconsin]] border, connecting with a county road.<ref name=\"MSHD52-04\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1952-04-15 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref> This segment of the highway (now Gogebic CR&nbsp;519)<ref name=\"googleW\">{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Wakefield,+MI&ie=UTF8&z=13&iwloc=addr |title=Wakefield, Michigan |access-date= March 16, 2008 }}</ref> was transferred back to the county in 1962.<ref name=\"MSHD62\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1962 |sections=B1\u2013B11}}</ref> M-94 previously looped along Munising-Van Meer-Shingleton Road (now [[H-58 (Michigan county highway)|H-58]] and [[H-15 (Michigan county highway)|H-15]]) north of M-28 between Munising and Shingleton. This routing was abandoned on November 7, 1963 in favor of the current [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]].<ref name=\"ROWAC\">{{cite map |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |map-url = http://mdotwas1.mdot.state.mi.us/public/ROWFiles/files/Alger/Sheet056.pdf |map = Alger County |title = Right-of-Way File Application |date =  |sheet = 56 |scale = Scale not given |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |access-date = May 8, 2008 |map-format = PDF |oclc = 23853690 }}</ref> The last significant change to the M-28 routing occurred on March 3, 1989, when the eastern terminus was moved east to [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]].<ref name=\"ROWCC\">{{cite map |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |mapurl = http://mdotwas1.mdot.state.mi.us/public/ROWFiles/files/Titlesheets/Chippewa.pdf |map = Chippewa County |title = Right-of-Way File Application |at = Title sheet |access-date = May 8, 2008 |date = August 7, 1991 |map-format = PDF |scale = Scale not given |oclc = 12843824 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:US 41 M-28 Marquette roundabout.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the roundabout in Marquette as proposed]]\nMDOT unveiled plans on March 31, 2009, to rebuild the intersection between Front Street and the eastern end of the Marquette Bypass during 2010.<ref name=diem-2009-03-27>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/524905.html?nav=5006 |title = City Set to Upgrade Confusing Intersection |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |access-date = April 2, 2009 |date = March 27, 2009 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDsgMpd8?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/524905.html?nav=5006 |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> The previous intersection configuration dated back to the 1960s and had been labeled as \"dangerous and [causing] significant traffic delays\" by the designers of the replacement.<ref name=diem-2009-04-02>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |url = http://www.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/525269.html?nav=5006 |title = Residents Get Look at Plan for Roundabout |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = The Mining Journal |access-date = April 2, 2009 |date = April 1, 2009 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> A traffic study concluded in 2007 that the intersection would need either the roundabout or a traffic signal with several turning lanes to accommodate the traffic needs in the area. MDOT decided in favor of a two-lane, {{convert|150|ft|m|adj=on}} roundabout retaining the right-turn lanes from the previous intersection layout. These lanes will be used by right-turning traffic to bypass the circle at the center of the intersection.<ref name=diem-2009-04-02/>\n\nConstruction started on the project in May.<ref name=diem-2010-06-21>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Roundabout Work Progresses |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = June 21, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/545490.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDt6QdUL?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/545490.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> A section of the intersection was opened in July to traffic from the south that turns west.<ref name=diem-2010-07-17>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Routes Through Town Reopen |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = July 17, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/546414.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtG6MSF?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/546414.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> The lanes northbound into downtown were opened in the beginning of August,<ref name=diem-2010-08-06>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = Open for Business: Motorists Take Measure of New Intersection |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = August 6, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547215.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtKFT6l?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547215.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref> and the city held a ribbon cutting ceremony on August 19, 2010. The remaining lanes were opened the next day.<ref name=diem-2010-08-19>{{cite news |last = Diem |first = Christopher |title = New Roundabout Celebrated with Ceremony |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = August 19, 2010 |url = http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547668.html |access-date = September 11, 2010 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wDtOKia0?url=http://beta249.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/547668.html |archivedate = February 3, 2011 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 |url-status = dead |df = }}</ref>\n\n=== Historic bridges ===\nMDOT has highlighted five [[National Register of Historic Places|historic]] bridges along the route of M-28 on the MDOT website. In [[Interior Township, Michigan|Interior Township]], [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]], the highway crosses the [[Ontonagon River]] over a bridge built in 1929.  Designed by the State Highway Department and built by the firm of Meads and Anderson, the Ontonagon River Bridge is one of only three [[Arch bridges|steel arch]] bridges in Michigan. The main span arch is  {{convert|150|ft|m|0}} long.<ref name=\"mb1\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013Ontonagon River Bridge |date = April 19, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-29212--,00.html |access-date = January 28, 2008 }}</ref> A former routing of M-28 in [[Covington Township, Michigan|Covington Township]] crosses the Rock River. Although this section was bypassed by a new alignment of the trunkline in 1924, the bridge remains complete \"with corbeled bulkheads and six panels recessed in the concrete spandrel walls.\"<ref name=\"mb2\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = Old M-28\u2013Rock River Bridge |date = April 9, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-25653--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> The [[corbel]]s and [[spandrel]]s are decorative features found in the concrete sides of the bridge.\n\n[[Image:US 41 Peshekee Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Abandoned Peshekee River Bridge in [[Michigamme Township, Michigan|Michigamme Township]]|alt=A river flowing between two banks covered in vegetation and trees. The river flows under a concrete bridge resting on four support piers into a lake in the background.]]\n\nToday, drivers cannot use the [[Trunk Line Bridge No. 1|Peshekee River Bridge]] south of US&nbsp;41/M-28 in western [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]]'s [[Michigamme Township, Michigan|Michigamme Township]]. The bridge was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1999 as \"Trunk Line Bridge No. 1\" for its engineering and architectural significance.<ref name=\"NHS1\">{{cite web |author = National Park Service |title = National Register of Historic Places\u2014Michigan (MI), Marquette County |year = 1999 |work = [[National Register of Historic Places]] |url = http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/MI/Marquette/state.html |access-date = February 12, 2008 |author-link = National Park Service }}</ref> MDOT has listed it as \"one of Michigan's most important vehicular bridges.\"<ref name=\"mb3\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = US&nbsp;41\u2013Peshekee River Bridge |date = April 23, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-30382--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> It was the first bridge designed by the Michigan State Highway Department, the forerunner to MDOT, in 1914. It was bypassed by a newer bridge built over the Peshekee River on US&nbsp;41/M-28 subsequently abandoned as a roadway. The replacement bridge was bypassed and demolished in 1995.<ref name=\"AL&S\">{{cite web |author = A. Lindberg & Sons, Inc. |title = Projects |publisher = A. Lindberg & Sons, Inc |url = http://www.lindberginc.com/projects.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060619055255/http://lindberginc.com/projects.htm |archivedate = June 19, 2006 |access-date = February 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe next historic bridge listed by MDOT along M-28 is [[M-28\u2013Sand River Bridge|over the Sand River]] in [[Onota Township, Michigan|Onota Township]] in [[Alger County, Michigan|Alger County]]. While not visible to motorists, the bridge, constructed in 1939, is the longest rural rigid-frame span in Michigan.<ref name=\"mb4\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013Sand River Bridge |date = April 9, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-25541--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> Most bridges of this type were built in urban locations, and soil conditions in the state limit locations for this style of bridge. The [[M-28\u2013Tahquamenon River Bridge|bridge]] over the East Branch of the [[Tahquamenon River]] in [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] was built in 1926 as a \"formative exercise in what would evolve into a state standard design.\"<ref name=\"mb5\">{{cite web |author = Michigan Department of Transportation |title = M-28\u2013E. Br. Tahquamenon River Bridge |date = April 15, 2002 |work = Michigan's Historic Bridges |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11154_11188-26681--,00.html |access-date = January 18, 2008 }}</ref> The {{convert|55|ft|m|0|adj=on}} bridge was built with nine lines of [[I-beam]]s encased in concrete. Only one other bridge in Michigan was built with such concrete encasement.<ref name=\"mb5\"/>\n\n== Future ==\n[[File:Michigan 480 Marquette County.svg|thumb|left|80px|CR&nbsp;480 in Marquette County|alt=County Road 480 marker]]\nIn the August 24, 2005 edition, the [[Marquette, Michigan|Marquette]] ''Mining Journal''  reported that the [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]] Board and the County Road Commission were negotiating with MDOT to transfer the jurisdiction of Marquette County Road&nbsp;480 to the state. Several routing options have been discussed, though all would make CR&nbsp;480 a part of M-28.<ref name=\"mj\">{{cite news |first = Pete |last = Mackin |title = CR&nbsp;480 Plan Taking Shape |location = Marquette, Michigan |work = The Mining Journal |date = August 24, 2005 |pages = A1+ |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> Cost was the primary reason given behind rerouting M-28 along CR&nbsp;480. \"The road commission receives about $50,000{{#tag:ref|Equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US-GDP|50000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}.{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}|group=lower-alpha}} a year in state gas tax money but spends about $100,000{{#tag:ref|Equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US-GDP|100000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}.{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}|group=lower-alpha}} to maintain CR&nbsp;480 because of the type and volume of traffic it receives.\"<ref name=\"mj\"/> Handing CR&nbsp;480 over to the state would shift the maintenance costs to the state, as well.<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\nMDOT has indicated that it has not requested jurisdiction, but rather if it assumed control of the route, the community would need to support a through-route. Several proposals have arisen, including creating a \"spur\" from US&nbsp;41/M-28 through the east end of Ishpeming to meet CR&nbsp;480 west of Negaunee. This spur would pass through recently reopened former mining \"caving grounds\", and to the south of the Mather A & B Mine complex.<ref name=\"mj\"/> According to Gerry Corkin, Marquette County Board Chairman, \"the land that was purchased by Ishpeming and Negaunee, the mining company land, this has the potential to help in the development of that if this is compatible. I think both cities will be interested in taking a look at what the land uses are and where this [spur] would push through.\"<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\nThe spur proposal would open land to development between the downtown areas of the two cities. If jurisdiction is transferred, and M-28 is routed over CR&nbsp;480 as proposed, M-28 would leave the concurrency with US&nbsp;41 near [[Teal Lake (Michigan)|Teal Lake]] in Negaunee, and cross the caving grounds west of downtown to connect to Rail Street. Rail Street would serve as the connector to CR&nbsp;480, which ends at the intersection of Rail and Ann streets and Healey Avenue. Proposals indicate two routing options for the east end of CR&nbsp;480. One would route M-28 back along US&nbsp;41 from Beaver Grove north of the CR&nbsp;480 eastern terminus to the existing M-28 in Harvey. A second would route it along CR&nbsp;551/Cherry Creek Road from CR&nbsp;480 to M-28 in Harvey.<ref name=\"mj\"/>\n\n== Business loops ==\n{{Main article|U.S. Route 41 Business (Marquette, Michigan)| M-28 Business (Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee, Michigan)| M-28 Business (Newberry, Michigan) |l1=Business US&nbsp;41 in Marquette|l2=Business M-28 in Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|l3=Business M-28 in Newberry}}\nThere have been three [[business loop]]s for M-28: Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee, Marquette and Newberry. Only the business loop serving Ishpeming and Negaunee is still a state-maintained trunkline. US&nbsp;41/M-28 was relocated to bypass the two cities' downtowns in 1937.<ref name=\"MSHD37-12\"/><ref name=\"MSHD37-05\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1937-05-15 |section= B5}}</ref> The highway through downtown Ishpeming and Negaunee later carried the ALT&nbsp;US&nbsp;41/ALT&nbsp;M-28 designation before being designated Bus. M-28 in 1958.<ref name=\"MDOT51\">{{cite map |author = Michigan State Highway Department |location = Lansing |publisher = Michigan State Highway Department |title = City of Ishpeming Act 51 Map |year = 1951 |scale = Scale not given }}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD58\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1958 |section=C5}}</ref> The western end of the business loop was transferred to local government control when Bus. M-28 was moved along Lakeshore Drive in 1999.<ref name=\"MSABR\">{{cite web |author = State Administrative Board |date = n.d. |title = State Administrative Board Resolutions, 1940\u2013Present |location = Lansing |publisher = State of Michigan |url = http://www.michigan.gov/documents/resolution_list_155716_7.pdf |access-date = February 13, 2008 |author-link = Michigan State Administrative Board }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marquette, Michigan - Buildings.jpg|thumb|right|The former Bus. US&nbsp;41 along Washington Street in downtown Marquette|alt=A city street with parked vehicles on either side in front of a series of stone buildings]]\nBus. US&nbsp;41 in Marquette was first shown on a map in 1964 after the construction of the Marquette Bypass.<ref name=\"MSHD63\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1963 |section=B6}}</ref><ref name=\"MSHD64\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1964 |section=B6}}</ref> It was later designated Bus. US&nbsp;41/Bus. M-28 on a map in 1975;<ref name=\"MDOT75\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 1975 |inset= Marquette}}</ref> this second designation was removed from maps by 1982.<ref name=\"MDOT82M\">{{cite MDOT map |year=1982 |inset= Marquette}}</ref> The entire business loop was turned back to local control in a \"route swap\" between the City of Marquette and MDOT announced in early 2005. The proposal transferred jurisdiction on the unsigned [[M-554 (Michigan highway)|M-554]] and the business route from the state to the city. The state would take jurisdiction over a segment of McClellan Avenue to be used to extend [[M-553 (Michigan highway)|M-553]] to US&nbsp;41/M-28. In addition, MDOT would pay $2.5&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|2500000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}) for reconstruction work planned for 2007.<ref name=\"swanson\">{{cite news |last = Swanson |first = Scott |title = City to Get $2.5&nbsp;Million |work = The Mining Journal |location = Marquette, Michigan |date = April 26, 2005 |page = A1 |issn = 0898-4964 |oclc = 9729223 }}</ref> The transfer would increase Marquette's operational and maintenance liability expenses by $26,000 (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US-GDP|26000|2005|r=-3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP|lastauthoramp=yes}}) and place the financial burden of the future replacement of a stop light on the city.<ref name=\"swanson\"/> On October 10, 2005, MDOT and Marquette transferred jurisdiction over the three roadways. As a result, Bus. US&nbsp;41 was decommissioned when the local government took control over Washington and Front streets.<ref name=\"jtpr\">{{cite press release |last = Garner |first = Dawn |title = MDOT and City of Marquette Complete Jurisdictional Transfer |publisher = Michigan Department of Transportation |date = November 9, 2005 |url = http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9620_11057-129975--,00.html |access-date = July 31, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070314203544/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0%2C1607%2C7-151-9620_11057-129975--%2C00.html |archivedate = March 14, 2007 |df = }}</ref> As a result of the decommissioning, the 2006 maps did not show the now former business loop.<ref name=\"MDOT06\">{{cite MDOT map |year=2006 |section=B4}}</ref>\n\nThe Newberry Bus. M-28 was designated from 1936 until 1952 as M-28A.<ref name=\"MSHD36-12\"/> The MSHD maps of the time showed it signed as Bus. M-28 in 1952 before it was turned back to local control in 1953.<ref name=\"MSHD53\"/><ref name=\"MSHD52-10\">{{cite MDOT map |date= 1952-10-01 |sections= B1\u2013B11}}</ref>\n\n== Major intersections ==\n{{MIinttop|ref=<ref name=\"PRFA\">{{cite MDOT PRFA |link= yes |access-date= April 13, 2010}}</ref>}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Gogebic\n|location=Wakefield\n|type=concur\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|2|Tour|LSCT|dir2=west|name2=Putnam Street|city1=Ironwood|city2=Iron River}}<br/>{{jct|state=MI|CR|519|county1=Gogebic|dir1=south|name1=Sunday Lake Street|nolink1=y}}\n|notes=Western end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Ontonagon\n|cspan=3\n|location=Merriweather\n|mile=16.281\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|64|dir1=south|city1=Marenisco}}\n|notes=Western end of M-64 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bergland\n|mile=20.422\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|64|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=White Pine|city2=Ontonagon|name2=Ash Street}}\n|notes=Eastern end of M-64 and LSCT concurrencies }}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bruce Crossing\n|mile=39.990\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|45|city1=Ontonagon|city2=Watersmeet}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Houghton\n|location=Kenton\n|type=concur\n|mile=56.394\n|mile2=56.596\n|road={{jct|state=MI|FFH|16}}\n|notes=Marked as H-16 on MDOT maps; short concurrency through Kenton}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Baraga\n|cspan=2\n|location=Covington\n|lspan=2\n|mile=74.330\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|141|dir1=south|city1=Crystal Falls|city2=Iron Mountain}}\n|notes=Western end of US&nbsp;141 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=78.484\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|41|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Baraga|city2=Houghton}}<br/>{{jct|state=MI|US|141|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US&nbsp;141; western end of US&nbsp;41 and LSCT concurrencies}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Marquette\n|cspan=10\n|location=Humboldt Township\n|mile=106.927\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|95|dir1=south|city1=Republic|city2=Iron Mountain}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-95}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Ishpeming\n|mile=118.614\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M-Bus|28|dab1=Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|name1=Lakeshore Drive|city1=Ishpeming}}\n|notes=Western terminus of Bus. M-28}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Negaunee\n|lspan=2\n|mile=122.215\n|road={{jct|state=MI|MI-Bus|28|dab1=Ishpeming\u2013Negaunee|name1=Teal Lake Avenue|city1=Negaunee}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Bus. M-28}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=122.957\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CR|492|county1=Marquette|dir1=east|name1=Maas Street|city1=Marquette}}\n|notes=Former routing along Marquette\u2013Negaunee Road}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Negaunee Township\n|mile=125.840\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|35|dir1=south|city1=Palmer|city2=Gwinn}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-35}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Marquette Township\n|ctdab=Marquette\n|mile=130.486\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CR|492|county1=Marquette|city1=Negaunee}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Marquette\n|lspan=3\n|mile=131.930\n|road=Washington Street\n|notes=Western terminus of former [[U.S. Route 41 Business (Marquette, Michigan)|Bus. US&nbsp;41]]}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=132.312\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|553|dir1=south|city1=KI Saywer|city2=Gwinn|name1=McClellan Avenue}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-553}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=133.674\n|road=Front Street\n|notes=Eastern terminus of former Bus. US&nbsp;41}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Harvey\n|mile=137.925\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|US|41|dir1=south|city1=Escanaba}}\n|notes=Eastern end of US&nbsp;41 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Alger\n|cspan=6\n|location=Onota Township\n|mile=159.637\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-01|dir1=south|city1=Chatham|name1=Rock River Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of H-01}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Au Train\n|mile=164.541\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-03|dir1=south|city1=Au Train|county1=Alger|name1=Au Train Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of H-03}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Munising\n|mile=175.903\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-58|county1=Alger|dir1=east|city1=Grand Marais|name1=Munising Road}}\n|notes=Western terminus of H-58<br />Provides access to [[Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Munising Township\n|mile=176.939\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|94|dir1=west|city1=Chatham}}\n|notes=Western end of M-94 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Wetmore\n|mile=178.849\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-13|FFH|13|county1=Alger|city1=Nahma|name2=Connors Road}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Shingleton\n|mile=186.409\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|94|CDH|H-15|county2=Alger|dir1=south|dir2=north|city1=Manistique|city2=Van Meer|name2=Van Meer Road}}\n|notes=Eastern end of M-94 concurrency<br />Western end of the Seney Stretch}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Schoolcraft\n|cspan=3\n|location=Hiawatha Township\n|mile=195.595\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-52|county1=Schoolcraft|dir1=north}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Seney\n|lspan=2\n|mile=210.984\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|77|dir1=south|city1=Blaney Park}}\n|notes=Eastern end of the Seney Stretch<br />Eastern end of a {{convert|0.36|mi|adj=on}} concurrency to cross Fox River}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=211.344\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|77|Tour|LSCT-Spur|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Grand Marais}}\n|notes=Western end of M-77 concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Luce\n|cspan=3\n|location=Lakefield Township\n|ctdab=Luce\n|mile=226.619\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-33|county1=Luce|dir1=south|city1=Germfask|name1=CR&nbsp;135 / Manistique Lakes Road}}\n|notes=Former terminus of [[M-135 (Michigan highway)|M-135]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Pentland Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=230.927\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|117|dir1=south|city1=Engadine}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of M-117}}\n{{MIint\n|type=concur\n|mile=233.916\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|123|Tour|LSCT|dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=Newberry|name2=Newberry Avenue}}\n|notes=Western junction with M-123; eastern end of LSCT concurrency; provides access to [[Tahquamenon Falls State Park]]}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Chippewa\n|cspan=5\n|location=Chippewa Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|type=concur\n|mile=257.648\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|123|Tour|LSCT|dir2=north|city1=Paradise|city2=Trout Lake}}\n|notes=Eastern junction with M-123; western end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Superior Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|mile=279.943\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|221|dir1=north|city1=Brimley}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of M-221}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Dafter Township\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=287.484\n|road={{jct|state=MI|I|75|Tour|LSCT|dir2=north|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace}}\n|notes=Exit 386 on I-75; eastern end of LSCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|mile=287.873\n|road={{jct|state=MI|CDH|H-63|county1=Chippewa|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace|name1=[[Mackinac Trail]]}}\n|notes=Former [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]]}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Bruce Township\n|ctdab=Chippewa\n|mile=290.373\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|129|Tour|LHCT|city1=Sault Ste. Marie|city2=St. Ignace|name1=McKnight Road}}\n|notes=}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Michigan Highways}}\n*[[List of longest state highways in the United States]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|M-28 (Michigan highway)|M-28}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title, inline}}\n*{{Osmrelation-inline|226345|M-28}}\n* [http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-028.html M-28] at Michigan Highways\n* [http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-178.html Former M-178] at Michigan Highways\n<!--* [http://www.state-ends.com/michigan/m/28/ M-28] at Michigan Highway Ends-->\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M028}}\n[[Category:M-28 (Michigan highway)|*]]\n[[Category:State highways in Michigan|028]]\n[[Category:Lake Superior Circle Tour]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Gogebic County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Ontonagon County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Houghton County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Baraga County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Marquette County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Alger County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Schoolcraft County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Luce County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Chippewa County, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-28_(Michigan_highway)"}
